{"title_page": "Trillium Line", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=the [[Trillium Railway]], a short-line in Ontario's Niagara region}}\n{{short description|Rapid transit line in Ottawa, Ontario}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox rail line <!-- already shown as \"Infobox public transit\" in [[O-Train|Lines]] -->\n| name            = \n| color           = {{OC Transpo color|2}}\n| logo            = {{rail-interchange|ottawa|2|size=35}}<br />[[File:Ligne Trillium Line logo.svg|frameless|upright=0.7]]\n| logo_width      = \n| image           = [[File:O-Train after Bayview Station 16171195227.jpg|frameless|upright=1.3]]\n| caption         = Train departing [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview station]]\n| system          = [[O-Train]]\n| type            = [[Light rail]]\n| locale          = [[Ottawa]], Ontario\n| start           = \n| end             = \n| stations        = 5 (+8 under construction)\n| routes          = \n| daily_ridership = 16,900 (avg. weekday, Q4 2017)<ref name=\"APTA-2017-Q4\">{{cite web | url = http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2017-q4-ridership-APTA.pdf | title = Transit Ridership Report Fourth Quarter and End-of-Year 2017 | publisher = [[American Public Transportation Association]] (APTA) | quote = (via: http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Pages/ridershipreport.aspx ) | format = pdf | page = 33 | accessdate = 2019-02-26 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180327084719/http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2017-Q4-Ridership-APTA.pdf | archive-date = March 27, 2018 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n| ridership2      = 4.194{{nbsp}}million (2017)<ref name=\"APTA-2017-Q4\" />\n| website         = [http://www.octranspo.com/routes?rte=2 O-Train Trillium Line]\n| open            = October 15, 2001\n| close           = \n| owner           = [[City of Ottawa]]\n| operator        = [[OC Transpo]] under the name Capital Railway\n| character       = \n| stock           = {{ubl|[[Alstom Coradia LINT]]|[[Stadler FLIRT]] (future)}}\n| linelength      = {{convert|8|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| tracklength     = \n| tracks          = \n| gauge           = {{Track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| minradius       = \n| electrification = None\n| signalling      = {{ubl|Combination of [[Punktf\u00f6rmige Zugbeeinflussung|Indusi]] and [[Canadian Rail Operating Rules|CROR]]|[[Positive Train Control|PTC]] (future)}}\n| speed           = \n| elevation       = \n| map             = {{Trillium Line route diagram}}\n| map_state       = \n}}\n{{Infobox rail|railroad_name=Capital Railway|marks=CR|hq_city=[[Walkley Yard]]|locale=Ontario and Quebec|logo=Capital_Railway_Logo.png|logo_size=120}}\n\nThe '''Trillium Line''' ({{lang-fr|Ligne Trillium}}) is a diesel [[light rail]] transit (DLRT) service in [[Ottawa]], Ontario, Canada, operated by [[OC Transpo]]. The line is part of the [[O-Train]] light rail system.\n\nThe present line runs north\u2013south on a railway line, from [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview]] to [[Greenboro station|Greenboro]], a distance of approximately {{convert|8|km|mi|0}}. It is isolated from road traffic, but shared with other trains; after operating hours, the section of track south of Walkley Yard has been infrequently used by [[Ottawa Central Railway|Ottawa Central]] for freight service to the [[National Research Council of Canada|National Research Council]].\n\nBetween 2013 and 2015, there was an upgrade of the line, including the complete replacement of the train fleet, in order to cut wait times during peak periods from 15 minutes to 12 minutes and eventually to 8\u201310 minutes. The upgrade was also a precursor to extending the line southwards by four stations.<ref name=\"Improve-Service-2015\" />\n\nIn 2022, a {{convert|16|km|adj=on}} extension and upgrade to the existing line is expected to be completed, adding eight new stations and a connection to [[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/|title=Trillium Line South|last=|first=|date=|website=Stage 2 Ottawa|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109044015/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/|archive-date=November 8, 2019|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> The Trillium Line will be shutdown for two years beginning in May 2020 to accommodate construction of the extension.<ref name=\"CBC-shutdown-2019\">{{cite web |last1=Ramlakhan |first1=Krystalle |title=Students rail against longer-than-expected O-Train shutdown |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/frustrated-students-carleton-o-train-ottawa-lrt-delays-longer-shut-down-1.5031347 |website=CBC News |accessdate=28 October 2019 |date=February 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930001943/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/frustrated-students-carleton-o-train-ottawa-lrt-delays-longer-shut-down-1.5031347 |archive-date=September 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"OS-construction-2019\">{{cite web |title=Here's what's happening for Stage 2 LRT construction right now |url=https://ottawastart.com/heres-whats-happening-for-stage-2-lrt-construction-right-now/ |accessdate=October 28, 2019 |date=October 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028124110/https://ottawastart.com/heres-whats-happening-for-stage-2-lrt-construction-right-now/ |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Service ==\nThe Trillium Line operates on a [[Single-track railway|single-track]] rail line with five stations and three [[passing loop]]s. With the exception of {{stn|Carleton}}, all stations have only a single platform.\n\nIt is legally considered a federally-regulated mainline railway despite being used for local public transport purposes, and the service it provides is, in terms of its route and service frequency, more like that of an urban railway than a [[rapid transit|metro]] or [[tram]]way. The line is operated by the City of Ottawa under the official name \"Capital Railway\", which appears on the trains along with their regular logo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/283-r-2007|title=Decision No. 283-R-2007|date=2007-06-06|website=www.otc-cta.gc.ca|access-date=2019-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405201205/https://www.otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/283-r-2007|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Pilot project===\n<!--Other articles link to this section name. Thus, if you change this name, you must code an {{anchor}} for the old section name to avoid broken links.-->\nThe Trillium Line was introduced on October 15, 2001, as a pilot project to provide an alternative to the [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Transitway]] [[bus rapid transit]] on which Ottawa had long depended exclusively for its high-grade transit service. The single-track line operated with five stations and a single passing loop at [[Carleton station]].\n\nAs a pilot project, the Trillium Line system was built at the cost of {{CAD|21{{nbsp}}million|link=yes}}, relatively little compared with the hundreds of millions of dollars usually required to build a new transit line. It runs on an existing [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] track (Ellwood and [[Prescott, Ontario|Prescott]] subdivisions<ref name=\"NiagaraRails\">{{cite web|url=http://www.niagararails.com/cgi-bin/img.cgi?/maps/otawatrm.gif|title=Ottawa Railways|last=Duncan|first=Paul|work=NiagaraRails.com|format=GIF|accessdate=2009-01-12}}</ref>), so the only construction work necessary was to build the stations themselves and the passing tracks necessary to allow trains to operate in both directions.\n\nFrom 2001 until 2015,<ref name=\"2015-Launch\" /> the system used three diesel-powered [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]] [[Talent (train)|Talent BR643]] [[low-floor]] [[diesel multiple unit]] trains. It was, however, described as \"light rail\", partly because plans called for it to be extended into Ottawa\u2019s downtown as a tramway-like service, and partly because the Talent vehicles, though designed for mainline railways in Europe, are much smaller and lighter than most mainline trains in North America, and do not meet the [[Association of American Railroads#Functions|Association of American Railroads']] standards for [[Buff strength|crash strength]]. Ottawa is also authorized to run trains with only a single operator and no other crew, something rare on mainline railways in North America.\n\nUntil late 2014, the official name of the diesel-powered, north\u2013south line was \"O-Train\". After construction started on a second, east\u2013west light rail line (the [[Confederation Line]]), the O-Train name was applied to the entire system, and the north\u2013south line was renamed the \"Trillium Line\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/o-train-name-approved-for-ottawa-light-rail-system-1.2769049|title=O-Train name approved for Ottawa light rail system|date=September 17, 2014|newspaper=[[CBC News Network]]|accessdate=2014-12-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007113656/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/o-train-name-approved-for-ottawa-light-rail-system-1.2769049|archive-date=October 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Original service====\n[[File:Carletonstation.jpg|thumb|left|[[Carleton station|Carleton]] is the only station with two platforms. Note retractable platform extenders at solid yellow markings.]]\n[[File:OttawaO-TrainInterior.jpg|thumb|left|Interior of the Bombardier Talent carriages (2001\u20132015)]]\nTicketing on the Trillium Line originally worked entirely on a proof-of-payment basis; there were no ticket barriers or [[turnstile]]s, and the driver did not check fares. Occasionally, OC Transpo Special Constables or other employees prompted passengers for proof-of-payment. Tickets can be purchased from a vending machine on the platform, and certain bus passes are also valid for the Trillium Line. Trillium Line tickets were exchanged for bus transfers upon boarding a bus. Although bus transfers can be used to board the O-Train, prepaid bus tickets cannot.\n\nThe European trains are narrower than the North American standard. In order to enable night-time use of the line by standard-width freight services, retractable platform extenders are mounted at each station (other than Bayview which is constructed on its own private rail spur). Passengers gain access to the Trillium Line on these extenders. If the line is used for freight, the extenders are retracted allowing a wider train to pass through the station. The extender interface with the train has been refined over time, and cyclists and wheelchair users now have no trouble accessing the train.\n\nThe service frequency of a train every fifteen minutes made it possible to run the line with a fleet of just three trains (of which only two were in service at any given time) and a single track, apart from passing sidings at [[Carleton station]].\n\nThe Trillium Line hit the 1-millionth rider mark on May 29, 2002, the 5-millionth mark on January 21, 2005, and the 10-millionth in late 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.octranspo.com/routes/odometer_1_mil_km|title=OC Transpo - Odometer passes 1 Millionth KM!|date=|publisher=octranspo.com|accessdate=2010-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121137/http://www.octranspo.com/routes/odometer_1_mil_km|archive-date=January 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In mid-2011, the Trillium Line carried an average of approximately 12,000 riders each day.<ref name=\"24may\" />\n\n====Awards====\nIn June 2002, the O-Train Light Rail Transit project received the [[Canadian Urban Transit Association]]\u2019s Corporate Innovation Award.<ref name=\"O-Train Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/programs/environment-utsp-otrainlightrailproject-973.htm|title=O-Train Light Rail Project|accessdate=2011-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123114358/http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/programs/environment-utsp-otrainlightrailproject-973.htm|archive-date=January 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 16, 2003, the Ontario chapter of the [[American Public Works Association]] (APWA) presented the City of Ottawa, [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] and [[Morrison Hershfield]] with the APWA Public Works Project of the Year award in the transportation category. This award was established to highlight excellence in the management and administration of public works projects by recognizing the alliance between the managing agency, the consultant and the contractors who, working together, complete public works projects.<ref name=\"O-Train Award\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acec.ca/en/memberfirms/paidprofile.asp?track=dp&itemid=1254|title=Acec.ca|accessdate=2011-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724102819/http://www.acec.ca/en/memberfirms/paidprofile.asp?track=dp&itemid=1254|archive-date=July 24, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA third award the Trillium Line light rail transit project received was in May 2003, in the sustainable transportation category of the FCM-CH2M Hill Sustainable Community Awards.<ref name=\"O-Train Awards\" />\n\n====Criticism of pilot project====\nThe main complaints about the Trillium Line pilot have revolved around its placement and ridership levels. The Trillium Line's route was determined by existing railway tracks, rather than the parts of the city that needed public transport, which would have required new tracks to be laid. [[Carleton University]] students, however, benefited from the Trillium Line pilot project, as it connected the university to the busy [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Ottawa Transitway]] system.\n\nThe other criticism is that there is very low ridership of the trains compared to some very crowded bus lines such as the 90\u201399 series routes. One fully loaded Trillium Line train carries 285 passengers compared to 131 passengers for an [[articulated bus]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.octranspo.com/contacts/press_releases/2001/010405_LowFloorBuses.htm|title= OC Transpo adds new low-floor articulated buses to its fleet|publisher= OC Transpo|date= 2001-04-05|accessdate= 2009-01-12| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929105859/http://www.octranspo.com/contacts/press_releases/2001/010405_LowFloorBuses.htm| archivedate = September 29, 2007}}</ref> The O-Train schedule is limited by track capacity.\n\n====Early extension plans====\n{{main|O-Train#Early extension plans}}\nIn July 2006, Ottawa City Council approved a north\u2013south light rail expansion project. The project would have terminated diesel light rail service on the Trillium Line so as to reuse its right-of-way for a double-track, electric light rail line that would have extended west from the [[University of Ottawa]] to [[Bayview station (OC Transpo)|Bayview]] then south to [[Leitrim, Ontario|Leitrim]] and then west to [[Barrhaven]]. However, in December 2006, Ottawa City Council cancelled this project, thus leaving the diesel-powered Trillium Line unchanged.\n\n===Service improvements===\nOn May 18, 2011, OC Transpo approved a $200,000 study to expand the Trillium Line. The $59-million proposal included the purchase of six new trainsets and track improvements that would increase headways to eight minutes from fifteen.<ref name=\"24may\">{{cite web | url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/index.php?id=44&no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=13296&cHash=3d62410f22 | title=Ottawa O-Train extension proposed | publisher=Railway Gazette International | date=24 May 2011 | accessdate=2011-05-28 | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z1jhrY0i?url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/index.php?id=44 | archivedate=May 28, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref> The project would finally cost $60.3{{Nbsp}}million.<ref name=\"Improve-Service-2015\">{{cite web |url=http://ottawa.ca/en/news/new-trains-improve-o-train-trillium-line-service |title=New Trains improve O-Train Trillium Line service |publisher=[[City of Ottawa]] |date=March 2, 2015 |accessdate=2015-07-31}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2013, service on the Trillium Line was suspended for four months to implement service and track improvements such as new station platforms and two new passing tracks (near Brookfield and Gladstone).<ref name=\"Improve-Service-2015\"/><ref name=\"2013-Upgrade\">{{cite news |url=http://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/ottawa-s-o-train-back-on-track-1.1438643 |last=Hua |first=John |title=Ottawa's O-Train back on track |publisher=Bell Media |website=CTVNews.ca |date=September 3, 2013 |accessdate=2015-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906075120/http://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/ottawa-s-o-train-back-on-track-1.1438643 |archive-date=September 6, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Upgrades were also made to the signal system, train controls, stations, tracks and train yard. A new centralized traffic control system was installed to improve safety and efficiency.<ref name=\"Improve-Service-2015\"/> Six new [[Alstom Coradia LINT]] trainsets (replacing the three older Bombardier Talent units) and the two extra passing loops allowed the number of trains on the line to double to four.\n\nExpanded service began on March 2, 2015, but suffered numerous problems during the first week.<ref name=\"2015-Launch\">{{cite web | url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/o-train-service-suspended-day-after-launch-of-expanded-line | title=O-Train shut down day after launch of expanded line (with video) | publisher=The Ottawa Citizen | date=3 March 2015 | accessdate=2015-07-29 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209232207/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/o-train-service-suspended-day-after-launch-of-expanded-line | archive-date=February 9, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Although the changes were intended to improve frequency to eight minutes, the Trillium Line would ultimately operate at twelve minute frequency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.octranspo.com/route/rte-timetable-text?rte=2&lang=en&date=20190208|title=Line 2 O-Train schedule|website=octranspo.com|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Derailment ===\nOn August 11, 2014, train C3 derailed while traveling northbound over the switch just south of Carleton Station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/human-error-faulty-switch-caused-o-train-derailment|title=Human error, faulty switch caused O-Train derailment|work=Ottawa Citizen|last=Pearson|first=Matthew|date=August 22, 2014|access-date=2019-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217030258/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/human-error-faulty-switch-caused-o-train-derailment|archive-date=February 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The cause was determined to be a faulty spring switch that had not closed properly as well as the operator failing to follow regulations and physically inspect the switch after spotting a signal irregularity. No serious injuries occurred as a result of the derailment, however train C3 received damage and was taken out of service. C3 was never repaired and never returned to service<ref name=\"sold\" /> and as a result the line continued to operate with only two operational trains until the following March when the new Alstom LINT trains entered service. In June 2017, the spring switches at Carleton were replaced with powered switches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shadqadri.com/2017/06/09/o-train-service-adjustment-carleton-spring-switchpreventative-maintenance/|title=O-Train Service Adjustment \u2013 Carleton Spring Switch/Preventative Maintenance|last=shadqadri|date=2017-06-09|website=Shad Qadri|language=en|access-date=2019-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217142306/https://shadqadri.com/2017/06/09/o-train-service-adjustment-carleton-spring-switchpreventative-maintenance/|archive-date=February 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== <span id=\"Stage 2\"></span> Future ==\n\nAs part of the city's Stage 2 LRT project, the Trillium Line will be extended {{convert|16|km}} in the south, including a {{Convert|3|km|adj=on}} branch to [[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport]] and the E.Y. Centre, with four new stations at [[South Keys station|South Keys]], Leitrim, Bowesville and Limebank in [[Riverside South, Ottawa|Riverside South]]. There will be a new passing loop at South Keys station and the track will be fully doubled from the Leitrim Road overpass to Limebank station. The full extension will be grade separated. In addition, two more stations will be built along the existing portion of the line at Gladstone and Walkley.<ref name=\"Stage2South\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/ |title=Stage 2 - Trillium Line South |publisher=[[City of Ottawa]] |date=2015 |accessdate=2015-08-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924105550/http://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/ |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The project will also include a number of other significant upgrades including the lengthening of all existing passing loops, the purchase of seven new trains, the doubling in length of all existing platforms, the grade separation of the Ellwood diamond to allow Via trains to cross underneath the Trillium Line, the replacement of rail bridges above the Rideau River and the southeast transitway, the refurbishment and repair of the Dow's Lake rail tunnel, the conversion of the signalling system to an implementation of [[positive train control]], the construction of several new pedestrian tunnels and overpasses, and numerous guide way and vehicle rehabilitation projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Stage-2-LRT_Contract-Award_FAQ_20190305.pdf|title=FAQs: Stage 2 LRT Contract Award|page=12|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183352/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Stage-2-LRT_Contract-Award_FAQ_20190305.pdf|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The contract for this project was approved on March 7, 2019, by city council,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/city-council-approves-stage-2-of-lrt-1.4324703|title=City council approves stage 2 of LRT|website=CTV News Ottawa|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183350/https://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/city-council-approves-stage-2-of-lrt-1.4324703|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> with construction of the airport spur beginning in mid-2019. The project is expected to be completed by September 2022.\n\nThe {{convert|3|km||adj=on}} airport branch will run from Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport north to South Keys station, where riders will need to change trains to continue to [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview station]]. The city is not contributing any money to this spur, with the funding instead coming from the federal and provincial governments, as well as the airport authority.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Contract-Award-of-Ottawas-Stage-2-LRT-Project_Final.pdf|title=Contract Award of Ottawa\u2019s Stage 2 Light Rail Transit Projects and Related Matters|date=2019-02-22|page=10|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183352/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Contract-Award-of-Ottawas-Stage-2-LRT-Project_Final.pdf|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2019, the city announced that the selected proponent to construct the project was TransitNEXT, a wholly owned subsidiary of [[SNC-Lavalin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Project_Technical-Briefing-EN_Feb-22.pdf|title=Stage 2 Light Rail Transit Project|date=2019-02-22|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183351/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Project_Technical-Briefing-EN_Feb-22.pdf|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snclavalin.com/en/media/press-releases/2019/29-03-2019|title=TransitNEXT finalizes Contract for Trillium Line Extension Project|website=www.snclavalin.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> This decision was controversial as the federal government and SNC-Lavalin were involved in a political scandal at the time, which led to extra scrutiny by city councillors, with some calling for a delay on the vote to approve the contract in order to allow more time for review. Ultimately Council voted not to delay the approval and the contract was approved on March 7, 2019.<ref name=\":1\" /> It was later revealed that TransitNEXT's bid had not met the minimum technical scoring threshold in order to be considered, which continued the controversy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/snc-lavalin-did-not-score-70-per-cent-minimum-lrt2-1.5064746|title=SNC-Lavalin failed to meet technical threshold for $1.6B LRT contract: sources|last=Chianello|first=Joanne|date=2019-03-22|work=CBC|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815182622/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/snc-lavalin-did-not-score-70-per-cent-minimum-lrt2-1.5064746|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The city eventually explained that the decision to award the contract to TransitNEXT was done at the discretion of city staff to get a better deal for the city and was within the rules of the procurement process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-admits-it-let-snc-lavalin-through-stage-2-lrt-bidding-despite-lower-technical-score|title=City admits it let SNC-Lavalin through Stage 2 LRT bidding despite lower technical score|work=Ottawa Citizen|last=Willing|first=Jon|date=2019-08-02|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804053717/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-admits-it-let-snc-lavalin-through-stage-2-lrt-bidding-despite-lower-technical-score|archive-date=August 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> An investigation conducted by the city's auditor general later confirmed that the authority delegated by council gave city staff sole discretion on whether to allow a bid to proceed even if it had not met the minimum scoring threshold, and that staff had otherwise correctly followed the entire procurement process that had been approved by council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-followed-the-rules-in-selecting-snc-lavalin-for-lrt-stage-2-project-auditor-general-finds|title=City followed the rules in selecting SNC-Lavalin for LRT Stage 2 project, auditor general finds |work=Ottawa Citizen|date=November 26, 2019 |first=Jon |last=Willing |access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n\nWork on the Stage 2 extension began in mid-2019, starting with the clear-cutting of trees along the corridors that will be used by the extension. Construction of the airport spur is expected to be completed in 2020 to give the airport authority time to rebuild the terminal and connect it to the future station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/construction-of-lrt-phase-2-leaving-its-mark-on-the-city|title=Construction of LRT Stage 2 leaving its mark on the city |work=Ottawa Citizen |date=November 14, 2019 |first=Blair |last=Crawford  |access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/r-2019-73|title=Determination No. R-2019-73|last=Toolkit|first=Web Experience|date=2019-08-01|website=otc-cta.gc.ca|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Further extensions ===\nExtending the Trillium Line across the Ottawa River into [[Gatineau]] across the [[Prince of Wales Bridge (Canada)|Prince of Wales Bridge]] had been proposed as early as the original pilot project proposal. The city's certificate of fitness for the Trillium Line, issued by the Canadian Transportation Authority in 2001, indicates that it operates between the provinces of Ontario and Quebec, despite the line never having actually operated across the river.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/635-R-2006|title=Decision No. 635-R-2006|date=2006-11-17|website=otc-cta.gc.ca|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183358/https://otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/635-R-2006|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The city even considered converting the rail bridge into a pedestrian crossing at one point.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/ad-to-convert-rail-bridge-over-ottawa-river-posted-early-city-says-1.2940839|title=Ad to convert rail bridge over Ottawa River posted early, city says|last=Steele|first=Alistair|date=2015-02-02|work=CBC|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504010728/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/ad-to-convert-rail-bridge-over-ottawa-river-posted-early-city-says-1.2940839|archive-date=May 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> When the city announced the contract awards for Stage 2, it also presented a map of the O-Train network that included proposed extensions that would be a part of a Stage 3 phase, including extensions to Kanata, Barrhaven, and Gatineau.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Project_Technical-Briefing-EN_Feb-22.pdf|title=Stage 2 Light Rail Transit Project|date=2019-02-22|website=|page=109|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183351/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Project_Technical-Briefing-EN_Feb-22.pdf|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 24, 2019, the cities of Ottawa and Gatineau jointly announced that they no longer intended to use the Prince of Wales bridge for any kind of rail connection, citing capacity concerns at Bayview station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/ottawa-gatineau-prince-of-wales-bridge-1.5296186|title=Mayors rule out Prince of Wales Bridge for transit link|date=2019-09-24|website=CBC|access-date=2019-09-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925051531/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/ottawa-gatineau-prince-of-wales-bridge-1.5296186|archive-date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the announcement, the future of the bridge remains uncertain since city staff later indicated that the bridge is still in the city's long term transit plans, though it could be converted for use as a pedestrian bridge in the interim. More on the future of the bridge as a rail link will be announced in the second quarter of 2020 when the city of Gatineau will present the results of a long-term transit study.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://capitalcurrent.ca/prince-of-wales-bridge-back-on-track-as-future-rail-link/ |title=Prince of Wales Bridge back on track as future rail link |work=Capital Current |access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n\n==Stations==\n{{main|List of O-Train stations}}\n{{citations needed|section|date=December 2019}}\n{{As of|2019||df=}}, ticket barriers are installed and operational in all Line 2 stations.  They were initially installed in all stations except for Bayview in order to test the hardware and software of the fare gate system before it was installed in all thirteen stations on the Line 1 Confederation Line.\n\nThe Trillium Line stations have sheltered waiting areas for passengers, but at three stations, these are only large bus-style shelters beside the tracks. The exceptions are Carling, where an elevator building is required since the tracks are below street level, and Greenboro, where a covered walkway extends towards the nearby [[South Keys Shopping Centre]]. All stations have level boarding platforms to allow for [[wheelchair]] [[accessibility|access]] and easier boarding for all passengers.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Station\n!Notes\n|-\n|{{octs|Bayview}}\n|Provides an interchange with the [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Transitway]] and the [[Confederation Line]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.octranspo.com/en/ready-for-rail/bayview|title=Bayview|website=www.octranspo.com|access-date=2019-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008202252/https://www.octranspo.com/en/ready-for-rail/bayview|archive-date=October 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The station is located on a stub-end track branching off from the railway line, immediately under the Wellington Street and Transitway overpasses. It is currently the closest Trillium Line station to downtown Ottawa.\n|-\n|{{octs|Carling}}\n|Located at [[Carling Avenue]] and [[Preston Street (Ottawa)|Preston Street]]. South of Carling, the train enters a tunnel to pass under [[Dow's Lake]].\n|-\n|{{octs|Carleton}}\n|Serves [[Carleton University]] and has separate tracks and platforms for each direction. Until the upgrade of the line in 2013, this station had the only passing loop along the line. South of Carleton, the train crosses over the [[Rideau River]] on a bridge.\n|-\n|{{octs|Mooney's Bay}}\n|Located at [[Heron Road (Ottawa)|Heron Road]] and [[Bronson Avenue (Ottawa)|Bronson Avenue]], and primarily serves [[Government of Canada]] offices in the Confederation Heights area.\n|-\n|{{octs|Greenboro}}\n|Provides an interchange with a large Transitway station, which has a large [[park and ride]] lot and is located next to the South Keys Shopping Centre.  The Trillium Line platform is level with the pedestrian overpass crossing the Transitway.\n|}\n\n===Future stations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Station\n!Notes\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Main line\n|-\n|Gladstone\n|Originally planned to be part of the pilot project but was cut for budgetary reasons.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://ottawa.ca/calendar/ottawa/archives/rmoc/Regional_Council/09Sep98/Light.pdf|title=Light Rail Pilot Project: Recommended Service Concept and Cost Analysis|access-date=2019-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201065338/http://ottawa.ca/calendar/ottawa/archives/rmoc/Regional_Council/09Sep98/Light.pdf|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[passing loop]] was added in 2013 to increase train frequency and line capacity.<ref name=\"2013-Upgrade\" /> It is the site of a future station that will feature two platforms on a double track extending from approximately the Beech Street underpass all the way to the terminus at Bayview station.<ref name=\"Stage2South\" />\n|-\n|{{octs|Walkley}}\n|Originally planned to be part of the pilot project but was cut for budgetary reasons.<ref name=\":0\" /> A [[passing loop]] was added in 2013 just north of Walkley to increase train frequency and line capacity.<ref name=\"2013-Upgrade\" /> It is the site of a future station immediately South of Walkley Road and near the existing Transitway station.<ref name=\"Stage2South\" />\n|-\n|{{octs|South Keys}}\n|Future connection between the main Line 2 and the airport rail link.  It will be a centre platform station in the middle of a double tracked segment and include a pocket track just north of the station for storing a trainset on layup.  The rail link trains are projected to arrive and depart in sync with the Line 2 trains.\n|-\n|{{octs|Leitrim}}\n|Adjacent to the existing station and park-and-ride lot.  This station will feature two platforms and an expanded park-and-ride lot.\n|-\n|Bowesville\n|Located just east of Bowesville Road, will feature two platforms, and will be the site of a new park-and-ride lot.\n|-\n|Limebank\n|Located just west of Limebank Road and south of Earl Armstrong Road and will service the Riverside South community within an expansive area zoned for commercial and retail purposes.  It will be one of the only stations to feature a public washroom.\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Airport branch\n|-\n|Uplands\n|Will be built East of Uplands Drive next to the EY Centre and will feature two platforms.  It will be the location of the only passing loop on the spur.\n|-\n|{{octs|Airport}}\n|Will be located at the [[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport]] and built into the renovated terminal at the departures level.\n|}\n\n==Fleet==\n<!--Other articles link to this section name. Thus, if you change this name, you must code an {{anchor}} for the old section name to avoid broken links.-->\n[[File:Interior of O-Train Alstom Coradia LINT.jpg|thumb|right|Interior of Alstom Coradia LINT]]\nThe Trillium Line initially used three Bombardier Talent [[diesel multiple unit]] (DMU) trains for service. Each train (numbered C1\u2013C3)<ref name=\"sold\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.govdeals.com/index.cfm?fa=Main.Item&itemid=97&acctid=6620|title=Lot of Three (3) 1999 Bombardier Talent Trainsets and Parts - govdeals.com|website=www.govdeals.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013324/https://www.govdeals.com/index.cfm?fa=Main.Item&itemid=97&acctid=6620|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> consisted of three cars, with the front and rear powered and the centre towed. The trains were originally ordered by [[Deutsche Bahn]] and later delivered to OC Transpo. After being retired in 2015, the units were put up for auction multiple times<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-unloading-bombardier-trains-the-original-trillium-line-workhorses|title=City auctioning off Bombardier trains|work=Ottawa Citizen|last=Willing|first=Jon|date=2016-12-28|language=en|access-date=2019-02-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201065328/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-unloading-bombardier-trains-the-original-trillium-line-workhorses|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> before eventually being sold for [[Canadian dollar|C$]]25,200 on December 14, 2018.<ref name=\"sold\" />\n\nIn September 2011, [[Alstom]] announced that it would deliver six new two-car [[Alstom Coradia LINT|Coradia LINT]] train sets in 2013;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2011/9/oc-transpo-chooses-alstom-supply-six-new-commuter-trains-Ottawa/|title=OC Transpo chooses Alstom to supply six new commuter trains to Ottawa|date=2011-09-16|publisher=Alstom|accessdate=2012-07-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117034016/http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2011/9/oc-transpo-chooses-alstom-supply-six-new-commuter-trains-Ottawa/|archive-date=November 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> the trains were handed over to OC Transpo in June 2013.<ref name=\"alstom_train_hand_over\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2013/6/in-ottawa-alstom-introduces-first-european-style-commuter-trains-for-north-america/|title=In Ottawa, Alstom introduces first European-style commuter trains for North America|date=2013-06-25|publisher=[[Alstom]]|accessdate=2013-07-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816170114/http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2013/6/in-ottawa-alstom-introduces-first-european-style-commuter-trains-for-north-america/|archive-date=August 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> These trains were put into service on March 2, 2015, and the Bombardier Talent units were subsequently retired.<ref name=\"ottawacitizen.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/expanded-o-train-service-to-begin-on-monday |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327172415/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/expanded-o-train-service-to-begin-on-monday |archive-date=March 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Class\n!Image\n!Type\n!Number of doors\n!Top speed\n!Number\n!Routes operated\n!Built\n!Years of service\n|-\n|[[Bombardier Talent]]&nbsp;BR643\n|[[File:O-Train C3 at Walkley Yard.jpg|frameless|upright=0.8]]\n|[[Diesel multiple unit|DMU]]\n|3 per side\n|{{convert|100|km/h||abbr=on}}\n|{{nowrap|3 \u00d7 3 car units}}<br />(9 cars total)\n| Bayview\u2013Greenboro\n| 2001\n|2001\u20132015\n|-\n|[[Alstom Coradia LINT#LINT 41|Alstom Coradia LINT&nbsp;41]]\n|[[File:J95729 OnOCTotrain 20160815-113119.58 Bayview.jpg|frameless|upright=0.8]]\n|[[Diesel multiple unit|DMU]]\n|2 per side\n|{{convert|140|km/h||abbr=on}}\n|{{nowrap|6 \u00d7 2 pair units}} <br />(12 cars total)\n|Bayview\u2013Greenboro,<br />''South Keys\u2013Airport'' (future)\n|2013\n|2015\u2013present\n|}\n\n=== Future fleet ===\nOn May 3, 2018, it was announced that the city would be purchasing seven new [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] FLIRT trains to use on the extended Trillium Line after the completion of Stage 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/news/city-secures-funding-to-extend-o-train-trillium-line-to-the-heart-of-riverside-south/|title=City secures funding to extend O-Train Trillium Line to the heart of Riverside South|date=2018-05-10|website=stage2lrt.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815224841/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/news/city-secures-funding-to-extend-o-train-trillium-line-to-the-heart-of-riverside-south/|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> These trains will be approximately {{convert|80|m|ft|0}} long which is double the {{convert|41|m|ft|0|adj=on}} length of the current Coradia LINT trains. The new trains will operate alongside coupled pairs of the existing LINT trains on the main line as part of a mixed fleet. These vehicles will be manufactured in Switzerland before being transported to Canada for final assembly.<ref>{{Cite techreport|title=Report to: Council|page=52|date=22 February 2019|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Contract-Award-of-Ottawa%E2%80%99s-Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Projects-and-Related-Matters.pdf|accessdate=February 26, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226172820/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Contract-Award-of-Ottawa%E2%80%99s-Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Projects-and-Related-Matters.pdf|archivedate=February 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Class\n!Type\n!Number of doors\n!Top speed\n!Number\n!Routes operated\n!Entering service\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Stadler FLIRT|Stadler FLIRT3]]\n|[[Diesel multiple unit#Diesel\u2013electric|DEMU]]\n|8 per side\n|{{Convert|130|km/h||abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://documents.ottawa.ca/sites/default/files/Appendix%20C%20_Natural_and_Air_Quality_TRI_Provincial_EA_Addendum_Appendices.pdf#page=105|title=Appendix C \u2013 Trillium Line EA Addendum Supplementary Terrestrial Information (Ellwood Diamond, Walkley Yard, Bowesville and Limebank) Air Quality Report|access-date=September 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918091143/https://documents.ottawa.ca/sites/default/files/Appendix%20C%20_Natural_and_Air_Quality_TRI_Provincial_EA_Addendum_Appendices.pdf#page=105|archive-date=September 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|7 x 4 car units<br />(28 cars total, not including power packs)\n|Bayview\u2013Limebank (Stage 2)\n|2022\n|Announced on May 3, 2018. Will have a diesel-electric drive with the possibility of future electrification.\n|}\n\n==Facilities==\nTrain sets are stored at the [[Walkley Yard (OC Transpo)|Walkley Yard]] located northeast of the Greenboro station. Before their retirement, the Bombardier Talent trainsets were maintained by [[Bombardier Transportation]] at the Walkley facilities. Bombardier continues to perform maintenance of the Trillium Line fleet, which included standstill maintenance of the retired Bombardier Talent trains until March 8, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govdeals.com/index.cfm?fa=Main.Item&itemid=97&acctid=6620|title=Lot of Three (3) 1999 Bombardier Talent Trainsets and Parts - govdeals.com|website=www.govdeals.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013324/https://www.govdeals.com/index.cfm?fa=Main.Item&itemid=97&acctid=6620|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Walkley Yard was built in 1955 by the [[National Capital Commission]] for the [[Canadian National Railways]] and later sold to the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]]. The yard has enclosed buildings for repairs and outdoor storage tracks.\n\n=== Stage 2 replacement ===\nAs part of the Stage 2 project, a new maintenance facility will be built adjacent and to the west of the existing facilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Appendix7.pdf|title=Relocated Walkley Yard MSF, West of Albion Road|date=2016-01-17|access-date=2019-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223020424/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Appendix7.pdf|archive-date=February 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The construction of the new yard facilities began in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ottwatch.ca/meetings/file/627775#page=12|title=Transit Services 2020 Business Plan|last=|first=|date=2019-02-19|website=ottwatch.ca|page=12|url-status=live|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Confederation Line]]\n* [[Letsgomoose]]\n* [[Light rail in Canada]]\n* [[Light rail in North America]]\n* [[List of tram and light rail transit systems#North America|List of tram and light rail transit systems]]\n* [[Prince of Wales Bridge (Canada)#Future|Prince of Wales Bridge]]\n* [[Rapibus#OC Transpo network connection|Rapibus]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n* [http://www.octranspo.com/routes/o-train-trillium-line OC Transpo \u2013 O-Train Trillium Line (official site)]\n*[http://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/ Stage 2 - Trillium Line South] - A City of Ottawa site publicizing O-Train expansion proposals\n**[https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/lrt_stage2_south_en.png Map of expansion plan]\n* [http://www.ottawa.ca/calendar/ottawa/citycouncil/ttc/2002/12-04/ACS2002-TUP-TRN-0012.htm O-Train Evaluation Report]\n* [http://www.tc.gc.ca/programs/environment/UTSP/otrainlightrailproject.htm O-Train Light Rail Project Summary (Transport Canada)]\n* [http://esteemfoundation.org/emdx//rail/Talent/ O-Train construction pictures]\n*[https://churcher.crcml.org/candate/Otrain.htm Salient Features of the O TRAIN (Trillium) Route]\n\n{{OC Transpo}}\n\n[[Category:O-Train]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2001]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in Canada]]\n[[Category:Light rail in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=the [[Trillium Railway]], a short-line in Ontario's Niagara region}}\n{{short description|Rapid transit line in Ottawa, Ontario}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox rail line <!-- already shown as \"Infobox public transit\" in [[O-Train|Lines]] -->\n| name                            = \n| color                           = {{OC Transpo color|2}}\n| logo                            = {{rail-interchange|ottawa|2|size=35}}<br />[[File:Ligne Trillium Line logo.svg|frameless|upright=0.7]]\n| logo_width                      = \n| image                           = [[File:O-Train after Bayview Station 16171195227.jpg|frameless|upright=1.3]]\n| caption                         = Train departing [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview station]]\n| system                          = [[O-Train]]\n| type                            = [[Light rail]]\n| locale                          = [[Ottawa]], Ontario\n| start                           = \n| end                             = \n| stations                        = 5 (+8 under construction)\n| routes                          = \n| daily_ridership                 = 16,900 (avg. weekday, Q4 2017)<ref name=\"APTA-2017-Q4\">{{cite web | url = http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2017-q4-ridership-APTA.pdf | title = Transit Ridership Report Fourth Quarter and End-of-Year 2017 | publisher = [[American Public Transportation Association]] (APTA) | quote = (via: http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Pages/ridershipreport.aspx ) | format = pdf | page = 33 | accessdate = 2019-02-26 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180327084719/http://www.apta.com/resources/statistics/Documents/Ridership/2017-Q4-Ridership-APTA.pdf | archive-date = March 27, 2018 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n| ridership2                      = 4.194{{nbsp}}million (2017)<ref name=\"APTA-2017-Q4\" />\n| website                         = [http://www.octranspo.com/routes?rte=2 O-Train Trillium Line]\n| open                            = October 15, 2001\n| close                           = \n| owner                           = [[City of Ottawa]]\n| operator                        = [[OC Transpo]] under the name Capital Railway\n| character                       = \n| stock                           = {{plainlist|\n*[[Alstom Coradia LINT]]\n*[[Stadler FLIRT]] (future)\n}}\n| linelength                      = {{convert|8|km|mi|0|abbr=on}}\n| tracklength                     = \n| tracks                          = \n| gauge                           = {{Track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| minradius                       = \n| electrification                 = None\n| signalling                      = {{plainlist|\n*Combination of [[Punktf\u00f6rmige Zugbeeinflussung|Indusi]] and [[Canadian Rail Operating Rules|CROR]]\n* [[Positive Train Control|PTC]] (future)\n}}\n| speed                           = \n| elevation                       = \n| map                             = {{Trillium Line route diagram}}\n| map_state                       = \n}}\n{{Infobox rail|railroad_name=Capital Railway|marks=CR|hq_city=[[Walkley Yard]]|locale=Ontario and Quebec|logo=Capital_Railway_Logo.png|logo_size=120}}\n\nThe '''Trillium Line''' ({{lang-fr|Ligne Trillium}}) is a diesel [[light rail]] transit (DLRT) service in [[Ottawa]], Ontario, Canada, operated by [[OC Transpo]]. The line is part of the [[O-Train]] light rail system.\n\nThe present line runs north\u2013south on a railway line, from [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview]] to [[Greenboro station|Greenboro]], a distance of approximately {{convert|8|km|mi|0}}. It is isolated from road traffic, but shared with other trains; after operating hours, the section of track south of Walkley Yard has been infrequently used by [[Ottawa Central Railway|Ottawa Central]] for freight service to the [[National Research Council of Canada|National Research Council]].\n\nBetween 2013 and 2015, there was an upgrade of the line, including the complete replacement of the train fleet, in order to cut wait times during peak periods from 15 minutes to 12 minutes and eventually to 8\u201310 minutes. The upgrade was also a precursor to extending the line southwards by four stations.<ref name=\"Improve-Service-2015\" />\n\nIn 2022, a {{convert|16|km|adj=on}} extension and upgrade to the existing line is expected to be completed, adding eight new stations and a connection to [[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/|title=Trillium Line South|last=|first=|date=|website=Stage 2 Ottawa|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191109044015/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/|archive-date=November 8, 2019|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> The Trillium Line will be shutdown for two years beginning in May 2020 to accommodate construction of the extension.<ref name=\"CBC-shutdown-2019\">{{cite web |last1=Ramlakhan |first1=Krystalle |title=Students rail against longer-than-expected O-Train shutdown |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/frustrated-students-carleton-o-train-ottawa-lrt-delays-longer-shut-down-1.5031347 |website=CBC News |accessdate=28 October 2019 |date=February 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930001943/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/frustrated-students-carleton-o-train-ottawa-lrt-delays-longer-shut-down-1.5031347 |archive-date=September 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"OS-construction-2019\">{{cite web |title=Here's what's happening for Stage 2 LRT construction right now |url=https://ottawastart.com/heres-whats-happening-for-stage-2-lrt-construction-right-now/ |accessdate=October 28, 2019 |date=October 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191028124110/https://ottawastart.com/heres-whats-happening-for-stage-2-lrt-construction-right-now/ |archive-date=October 28, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Service ==\nThe Trillium Line operates on a [[Single-track railway|single-track]] rail line with five stations and three [[passing loop]]s. With the exception of {{stn|Carleton}}, all stations have only a single platform.\n\nIt is legally considered a federally-regulated mainline railway despite being used for local public transport purposes, and the service it provides is, in terms of its route and service frequency, more like that of an urban railway than a [[rapid transit|metro]] or [[tram]]way. The line is operated by the City of Ottawa under the official name \"Capital Railway\", which appears on the trains along with their regular logo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/283-r-2007|title=Decision No. 283-R-2007|date=2007-06-06|website=www.otc-cta.gc.ca|access-date=2019-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190405201205/https://www.otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/283-r-2007|archive-date=April 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Pilot project===\n<!--Other articles link to this section name. Thus, if you change this name, you must code an {{anchor}} for the old section name to avoid broken links.-->\nThe Trillium Line was introduced on October 15, 2001, as a pilot project to provide an alternative to the [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Transitway]] [[bus rapid transit]] on which Ottawa had long depended exclusively for its high-grade transit service. The single-track line operated with five stations and a single passing loop at [[Carleton station]].\n\nAs a pilot project, the Trillium Line system was built at the cost of {{CAD|21{{nbsp}}million|link=yes}}, relatively little compared with the hundreds of millions of dollars usually required to build a new transit line. It runs on an existing [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] track (Ellwood and [[Prescott, Ontario|Prescott]] subdivisions<ref name=\"NiagaraRails\">{{cite web|url=http://www.niagararails.com/cgi-bin/img.cgi?/maps/otawatrm.gif|title=Ottawa Railways|last=Duncan|first=Paul|work=NiagaraRails.com|format=GIF|accessdate=2009-01-12}}</ref>), so the only construction work necessary was to build the stations themselves and the passing tracks necessary to allow trains to operate in both directions.\n\nFrom 2001 until 2015,<ref name=\"2015-Launch\" /> the system used three diesel-powered [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]] [[Talent (train)|Talent BR643]] [[low-floor]] [[diesel multiple unit]] trains. It was, however, described as \"light rail\", partly because plans called for it to be extended into Ottawa\u2019s downtown as a tramway-like service, and partly because the Talent vehicles, though designed for mainline railways in Europe, are much smaller and lighter than most mainline trains in North America, and do not meet the [[Association of American Railroads#Functions|Association of American Railroads']] standards for [[Buff strength|crash strength]]. Ottawa is also authorized to run trains with only a single operator and no other crew, something rare on mainline railways in North America.\n\nUntil late 2014, the official name of the diesel-powered, north\u2013south line was \"O-Train\". After construction started on a second, east\u2013west light rail line (the [[Confederation Line]]), the O-Train name was applied to the entire system, and the north\u2013south line was renamed the \"Trillium Line\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/o-train-name-approved-for-ottawa-light-rail-system-1.2769049|title=O-Train name approved for Ottawa light rail system|date=September 17, 2014|newspaper=[[CBC News Network]]|accessdate=2014-12-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141007113656/http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/o-train-name-approved-for-ottawa-light-rail-system-1.2769049|archive-date=October 7, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Original service====\n[[File:Carletonstation.jpg|thumb|left|[[Carleton station|Carleton]] is the only station with two platforms. Note retractable platform extenders at solid yellow markings.]]\n[[File:OttawaO-TrainInterior.jpg|thumb|left|Interior of the Bombardier Talent carriages (2001\u20132015)]]\nTicketing on the Trillium Line originally worked entirely on a proof-of-payment basis; there were no ticket barriers or [[turnstile]]s, and the driver did not check fares. Occasionally, OC Transpo Special Constables or other employees prompted passengers for proof-of-payment. Tickets can be purchased from a vending machine on the platform, and certain bus passes are also valid for the Trillium Line. Trillium Line tickets were exchanged for bus transfers upon boarding a bus. Although bus transfers can be used to board the O-Train, prepaid bus tickets cannot.\n\nThe European trains are narrower than the North American standard. In order to enable night-time use of the line by standard-width freight services, retractable platform extenders are mounted at each station (other than Bayview which is constructed on its own private rail spur). Passengers gain access to the Trillium Line on these extenders. If the line is used for freight, the extenders are retracted allowing a wider train to pass through the station. The extender interface with the train has been refined over time, and cyclists and wheelchair users now have no trouble accessing the train.\n\nThe service frequency of a train every fifteen minutes made it possible to run the line with a fleet of just three trains (of which only two were in service at any given time) and a single track, apart from passing sidings at [[Carleton station]].\n\nThe Trillium Line hit the 1-millionth rider mark on May 29, 2002, the 5-millionth mark on January 21, 2005, and the 10-millionth in late 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.octranspo.com/routes/odometer_1_mil_km|title=OC Transpo - Odometer passes 1 Millionth KM!|date=|publisher=octranspo.com|accessdate=2010-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190119121137/http://www.octranspo.com/routes/odometer_1_mil_km|archive-date=January 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> In mid-2011, the Trillium Line carried an average of approximately 12,000 riders each day.<ref name=\"24may\" />\n\n====Awards====\nIn June 2002, the O-Train Light Rail Transit project received the [[Canadian Urban Transit Association]]\u2019s Corporate Innovation Award.<ref name=\"O-Train Awards\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/programs/environment-utsp-otrainlightrailproject-973.htm|title=O-Train Light Rail Project|accessdate=2011-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110123114358/http://www.tc.gc.ca/eng/programs/environment-utsp-otrainlightrailproject-973.htm|archive-date=January 23, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn January 16, 2003, the Ontario chapter of the [[American Public Works Association]] (APWA) presented the City of Ottawa, [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] and [[Morrison Hershfield]] with the APWA Public Works Project of the Year award in the transportation category. This award was established to highlight excellence in the management and administration of public works projects by recognizing the alliance between the managing agency, the consultant and the contractors who, working together, complete public works projects.<ref name=\"O-Train Award\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acec.ca/en/memberfirms/paidprofile.asp?track=dp&itemid=1254|title=Acec.ca|accessdate=2011-04-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724102819/http://www.acec.ca/en/memberfirms/paidprofile.asp?track=dp&itemid=1254|archive-date=July 24, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA third award the Trillium Line light rail transit project received was in May 2003, in the sustainable transportation category of the FCM-CH2M Hill Sustainable Community Awards.<ref name=\"O-Train Awards\" />\n\n====Criticism of pilot project====\nThe main complaints about the Trillium Line pilot have revolved around its placement and ridership levels. The Trillium Line's route was determined by existing railway tracks, rather than the parts of the city that needed public transport, which would have required new tracks to be laid. [[Carleton University]] students, however, benefited from the Trillium Line pilot project, as it connected the university to the busy [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Ottawa Transitway]] system.\n\nThe other criticism is that there is very low ridership of the trains compared to some very crowded bus lines such as the 90\u201399 series routes. One fully loaded Trillium Line train carries 285 passengers compared to 131 passengers for an [[articulated bus]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.octranspo.com/contacts/press_releases/2001/010405_LowFloorBuses.htm|title= OC Transpo adds new low-floor articulated buses to its fleet|publisher= OC Transpo|date= 2001-04-05|accessdate= 2009-01-12| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929105859/http://www.octranspo.com/contacts/press_releases/2001/010405_LowFloorBuses.htm| archivedate = September 29, 2007}}</ref> The O-Train schedule is limited by track capacity.\n\n====Early extension plans====\n{{main|O-Train#Early extension plans}}\nIn July 2006, Ottawa City Council approved a north\u2013south light rail expansion project. The project would have terminated diesel light rail service on the Trillium Line so as to reuse its right-of-way for a double-track, electric light rail line that would have extended west from the [[University of Ottawa]] to [[Bayview station (OC Transpo)|Bayview]] then south to [[Leitrim, Ontario|Leitrim]] and then west to [[Barrhaven]]. However, in December 2006, Ottawa City Council cancelled this project, thus leaving the diesel-powered Trillium Line unchanged.\n\n===Service improvements===\nOn May 18, 2011, OC Transpo approved a $200,000 study to expand the Trillium Line. The $59-million proposal included the purchase of six new trainsets and track improvements that would increase headways to eight minutes from fifteen.<ref name=\"24may\">{{cite web | url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/index.php?id=44&no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=13296&cHash=3d62410f22 | title=Ottawa O-Train extension proposed | publisher=Railway Gazette International | date=24 May 2011 | accessdate=2011-05-28 | archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5z1jhrY0i?url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/index.php?id=44 | archivedate=May 28, 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref> The project would finally cost $60.3{{Nbsp}}million.<ref name=\"Improve-Service-2015\">{{cite web |url=http://ottawa.ca/en/news/new-trains-improve-o-train-trillium-line-service |title=New Trains improve O-Train Trillium Line service |publisher=[[City of Ottawa]] |date=March 2, 2015 |accessdate=2015-07-31}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2013, service on the Trillium Line was suspended for four months to implement service and track improvements such as new station platforms and two new passing tracks (near Brookfield and Gladstone).<ref name=\"Improve-Service-2015\"/><ref name=\"2013-Upgrade\">{{cite news |url=http://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/ottawa-s-o-train-back-on-track-1.1438643 |last=Hua |first=John |title=Ottawa's O-Train back on track |publisher=Bell Media |website=CTVNews.ca |date=September 3, 2013 |accessdate=2015-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906075120/http://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/ottawa-s-o-train-back-on-track-1.1438643 |archive-date=September 6, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> Upgrades were also made to the signal system, train controls, stations, tracks and train yard. A new centralized traffic control system was installed to improve safety and efficiency.<ref name=\"Improve-Service-2015\"/> Six new [[Alstom Coradia LINT]] trainsets (replacing the three older Bombardier Talent units) and the two extra passing loops allowed the number of trains on the line to double to four.\n\nExpanded service began on March 2, 2015, but suffered numerous problems during the first week.<ref name=\"2015-Launch\">{{cite web | url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/o-train-service-suspended-day-after-launch-of-expanded-line | title=O-Train shut down day after launch of expanded line (with video) | publisher=The Ottawa Citizen | date=3 March 2015 | accessdate=2015-07-29 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190209232207/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/o-train-service-suspended-day-after-launch-of-expanded-line | archive-date=February 9, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> Although the changes were intended to improve frequency to eight minutes, the Trillium Line would ultimately operate at twelve minute frequency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.octranspo.com/route/rte-timetable-text?rte=2&lang=en&date=20190208|title=Line 2 O-Train schedule|website=octranspo.com|access-date=2019-02-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Derailment ===\nOn August 11, 2014, train C3 derailed while traveling northbound over the switch just south of Carleton Station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/human-error-faulty-switch-caused-o-train-derailment|title=Human error, faulty switch caused O-Train derailment|work=Ottawa Citizen|last=Pearson|first=Matthew|date=August 22, 2014|access-date=2019-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217030258/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/human-error-faulty-switch-caused-o-train-derailment|archive-date=February 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The cause was determined to be a faulty spring switch that had not closed properly as well as the operator failing to follow regulations and physically inspect the switch after spotting a signal irregularity. No serious injuries occurred as a result of the derailment, however train C3 received damage and was taken out of service. C3 was never repaired and never returned to service<ref name=\"sold\" /> and as a result the line continued to operate with only two operational trains until the following March when the new Alstom LINT trains entered service. In June 2017, the spring switches at Carleton were replaced with powered switches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shadqadri.com/2017/06/09/o-train-service-adjustment-carleton-spring-switchpreventative-maintenance/|title=O-Train Service Adjustment \u2013 Carleton Spring Switch/Preventative Maintenance|last=shadqadri|date=2017-06-09|website=Shad Qadri|language=en|access-date=2019-02-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190217142306/https://shadqadri.com/2017/06/09/o-train-service-adjustment-carleton-spring-switchpreventative-maintenance/|archive-date=February 17, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== <span id=\"Stage 2\"></span> Future ==\n\nAs part of the city's Stage 2 LRT project, the Trillium Line will be extended {{convert|16|km}} in the south, including a {{Convert|3|km|adj=on}} branch to [[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport|Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport]] and the E.Y. Centre, with four new stations at [[South Keys station|South Keys]], Leitrim, Bowesville and Limebank in [[Riverside South, Ottawa|Riverside South]]. There will be a new passing loop at South Keys station and the track will be fully doubled from the Leitrim Road overpass to Limebank station. The full extension will be grade separated. In addition, two more stations will be built along the existing portion of the line at Gladstone and Walkley.<ref name=\"Stage2South\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/ |title=Stage 2 - Trillium Line South |publisher=[[City of Ottawa]] |date=2015 |accessdate=2015-08-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924105550/http://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/ |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The project will also include a number of other significant upgrades including the lengthening of all existing passing loops, the purchase of seven new trains, the doubling in length of all existing platforms, the grade separation of the Ellwood diamond to allow Via trains to cross underneath the Trillium Line, the replacement of rail bridges above the Rideau River and the southeast transitway, the refurbishment and repair of the Dow's Lake rail tunnel, the conversion of the signalling system to an implementation of [[positive train control]], the construction of several new pedestrian tunnels and overpasses, and numerous guide way and vehicle rehabilitation projects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Stage-2-LRT_Contract-Award_FAQ_20190305.pdf|title=FAQs: Stage 2 LRT Contract Award|page=12|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183352/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Stage-2-LRT_Contract-Award_FAQ_20190305.pdf|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The contract for this project was approved on March 7, 2019, by city council,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/city-council-approves-stage-2-of-lrt-1.4324703|title=City council approves stage 2 of LRT|website=CTV News Ottawa|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183350/https://ottawa.ctvnews.ca/city-council-approves-stage-2-of-lrt-1.4324703|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> with construction of the airport spur beginning in mid-2019. The project is expected to be completed by September 2022.\n\nThe {{convert|3|km||adj=on}} airport branch will run from Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport north to South Keys station, where riders will need to change trains to continue to [[Bayview station (Ottawa)|Bayview station]]. The city is not contributing any money to this spur, with the funding instead coming from the federal and provincial governments, as well as the airport authority.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Contract-Award-of-Ottawas-Stage-2-LRT-Project_Final.pdf|title=Contract Award of Ottawa\u2019s Stage 2 Light Rail Transit Projects and Related Matters|date=2019-02-22|page=10|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183352/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Contract-Award-of-Ottawas-Stage-2-LRT-Project_Final.pdf|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2019, the city announced that the selected proponent to construct the project was TransitNEXT, a wholly owned subsidiary of [[SNC-Lavalin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Project_Technical-Briefing-EN_Feb-22.pdf|title=Stage 2 Light Rail Transit Project|date=2019-02-22|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183351/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Project_Technical-Briefing-EN_Feb-22.pdf|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.snclavalin.com/en/media/press-releases/2019/29-03-2019|title=TransitNEXT finalizes Contract for Trillium Line Extension Project|website=www.snclavalin.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> This decision was controversial as the federal government and SNC-Lavalin were involved in a political scandal at the time, which led to extra scrutiny by city councillors, with some calling for a delay on the vote to approve the contract in order to allow more time for review. Ultimately Council voted not to delay the approval and the contract was approved on March 7, 2019.<ref name=\":1\" /> It was later revealed that TransitNEXT's bid had not met the minimum technical scoring threshold in order to be considered, which continued the controversy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/snc-lavalin-did-not-score-70-per-cent-minimum-lrt2-1.5064746|title=SNC-Lavalin failed to meet technical threshold for $1.6B LRT contract: sources|last=Chianello|first=Joanne|date=2019-03-22|work=CBC|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815182622/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/snc-lavalin-did-not-score-70-per-cent-minimum-lrt2-1.5064746|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The city eventually explained that the decision to award the contract to TransitNEXT was done at the discretion of city staff to get a better deal for the city and was within the rules of the procurement process.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-admits-it-let-snc-lavalin-through-stage-2-lrt-bidding-despite-lower-technical-score|title=City admits it let SNC-Lavalin through Stage 2 LRT bidding despite lower technical score|work=Ottawa Citizen|last=Willing|first=Jon|date=2019-08-02|language=en|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804053717/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-admits-it-let-snc-lavalin-through-stage-2-lrt-bidding-despite-lower-technical-score|archive-date=August 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> An investigation conducted by the city's auditor general later confirmed that the authority delegated by council gave city staff sole discretion on whether to allow a bid to proceed even if it had not met the minimum scoring threshold, and that staff had otherwise correctly followed the entire procurement process that had been approved by council.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-followed-the-rules-in-selecting-snc-lavalin-for-lrt-stage-2-project-auditor-general-finds|title=City followed the rules in selecting SNC-Lavalin for LRT Stage 2 project, auditor general finds |work=Ottawa Citizen|date=November 26, 2019 |first=Jon |last=Willing |access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n\nWork on the Stage 2 extension began in mid-2019, starting with the clear-cutting of trees along the corridors that will be used by the extension. Construction of the airport spur is expected to be completed in 2020 to give the airport authority time to rebuild the terminal and connect it to the future station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/construction-of-lrt-phase-2-leaving-its-mark-on-the-city|title=Construction of LRT Stage 2 leaving its mark on the city |work=Ottawa Citizen |date=November 14, 2019 |first=Blair |last=Crawford  |access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/r-2019-73|title=Determination No. R-2019-73|last=Toolkit|first=Web Experience|date=2019-08-01|website=otc-cta.gc.ca|access-date=2019-11-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Further extensions ===\nExtending the Trillium Line across the Ottawa River into [[Gatineau]] across the [[Prince of Wales Bridge (Canada)|Prince of Wales Bridge]] had been proposed as early as the original pilot project proposal. The city's certificate of fitness for the Trillium Line, issued by the Canadian Transportation Authority in 2001, indicates that it operates between the provinces of Ontario and Quebec, despite the line never having actually operated across the river.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/635-R-2006|title=Decision No. 635-R-2006|date=2006-11-17|website=otc-cta.gc.ca|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183358/https://otc-cta.gc.ca/eng/ruling/635-R-2006|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The city even considered converting the rail bridge into a pedestrian crossing at one point.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/ad-to-convert-rail-bridge-over-ottawa-river-posted-early-city-says-1.2940839|title=Ad to convert rail bridge over Ottawa River posted early, city says|last=Steele|first=Alistair|date=2015-02-02|work=CBC|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190504010728/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/ad-to-convert-rail-bridge-over-ottawa-river-posted-early-city-says-1.2940839|archive-date=May 4, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> When the city announced the contract awards for Stage 2, it also presented a map of the O-Train network that included proposed extensions that would be a part of a Stage 3 phase, including extensions to Kanata, Barrhaven, and Gatineau.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Project_Technical-Briefing-EN_Feb-22.pdf|title=Stage 2 Light Rail Transit Project|date=2019-02-22|website=|page=109|access-date=2019-09-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901183351/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Project_Technical-Briefing-EN_Feb-22.pdf|archive-date=September 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On September 24, 2019, the cities of Ottawa and Gatineau jointly announced that they no longer intended to use the Prince of Wales bridge for any kind of rail connection, citing capacity concerns at Bayview station.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/ottawa-gatineau-prince-of-wales-bridge-1.5296186|title=Mayors rule out Prince of Wales Bridge for transit link|date=2019-09-24|website=CBC|access-date=2019-09-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925051531/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/ottawa/ottawa-gatineau-prince-of-wales-bridge-1.5296186|archive-date=September 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite the announcement, the future of the bridge remains uncertain since city staff later indicated that the bridge is still in the city's long term transit plans, though it could be converted for use as a pedestrian bridge in the interim. More on the future of the bridge as a rail link will be announced in the second quarter of 2020 when the city of Gatineau will present the results of a long-term transit study.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://capitalcurrent.ca/prince-of-wales-bridge-back-on-track-as-future-rail-link/ |title=Prince of Wales Bridge back on track as future rail link |work=Capital Current |access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n\n==Stations==\n{{main|List of O-Train stations}}\n{{citations needed|section|date=December 2019}}\n{{As of|2019||df=}}, ticket barriers are installed and operational in all Line 2 stations.  They were initially installed in all stations except for Bayview in order to test the hardware and software of the fare gate system before it was installed in all thirteen stations on the Line 1 Confederation Line.\n\nThe Trillium Line stations have sheltered waiting areas for passengers, but at three stations, these are only large bus-style shelters beside the tracks. The exceptions are Carling, where an elevator building is required since the tracks are below street level, and Greenboro, where a covered walkway extends towards the nearby [[South Keys Shopping Centre]]. All stations have level boarding platforms to allow for [[wheelchair]] [[accessibility|access]] and easier boarding for all passengers.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Station\n!Notes\n|-\n|{{octs|Bayview}}\n|Provides an interchange with the [[Transitway (Ottawa)|Transitway]] and the [[Confederation Line]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.octranspo.com/en/ready-for-rail/bayview|title=Bayview|website=www.octranspo.com|access-date=2019-10-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008202252/https://www.octranspo.com/en/ready-for-rail/bayview|archive-date=October 8, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The station is located on a stub-end track branching off from the railway line, immediately under the Wellington Street and Transitway overpasses. It is currently the closest Trillium Line station to downtown Ottawa.\n|-\n|{{octs|Carling}}\n|Located at [[Carling Avenue]] and [[Preston Street (Ottawa)|Preston Street]]. South of Carling, the train enters a tunnel to pass under [[Dow's Lake]].\n|-\n|{{octs|Carleton}}\n|Serves [[Carleton University]] and has separate tracks and platforms for each direction. Until the upgrade of the line in 2013, this station had the only passing loop along the line. South of Carleton, the train crosses over the [[Rideau River]] on a bridge.\n|-\n|{{octs|Mooney's Bay}}\n|Located at [[Heron Road (Ottawa)|Heron Road]] and [[Bronson Avenue (Ottawa)|Bronson Avenue]], and primarily serves [[Government of Canada]] offices in the Confederation Heights area.\n|-\n|{{octs|Greenboro}}\n|Provides an interchange with a large Transitway station, which has a large [[park and ride]] lot and is located next to the South Keys Shopping Centre.  The Trillium Line platform is level with the pedestrian overpass crossing the Transitway.\n|}\n\n===Future stations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Station\n!Notes\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Main line\n|-\n|Gladstone\n|Originally planned to be part of the pilot project but was cut for budgetary reasons.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://ottawa.ca/calendar/ottawa/archives/rmoc/Regional_Council/09Sep98/Light.pdf|title=Light Rail Pilot Project: Recommended Service Concept and Cost Analysis|access-date=2019-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201065338/http://ottawa.ca/calendar/ottawa/archives/rmoc/Regional_Council/09Sep98/Light.pdf|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[passing loop]] was added in 2013 to increase train frequency and line capacity.<ref name=\"2013-Upgrade\" /> It is the site of a future station that will feature two platforms on a double track extending from approximately the Beech Street underpass all the way to the terminus at Bayview station.<ref name=\"Stage2South\" />\n|-\n|{{octs|Walkley}}\n|Originally planned to be part of the pilot project but was cut for budgetary reasons.<ref name=\":0\" /> A [[passing loop]] was added in 2013 just north of Walkley to increase train frequency and line capacity.<ref name=\"2013-Upgrade\" /> It is the site of a future station immediately South of Walkley Road and near the existing Transitway station.<ref name=\"Stage2South\" />\n|-\n|{{octs|South Keys}}\n|Future connection between the main Line 2 and the airport rail link.  It will be a centre platform station in the middle of a double tracked segment and include a pocket track just north of the station for storing a trainset on layup.  The rail link trains are projected to arrive and depart in sync with the Line 2 trains.\n|-\n|{{octs|Leitrim}}\n|Adjacent to the existing station and park-and-ride lot.  This station will feature two platforms and an expanded park-and-ride lot.\n|-\n|Bowesville\n|Located just east of Bowesville Road, will feature two platforms, and will be the site of a new park-and-ride lot.\n|-\n|Limebank\n|Located just west of Limebank Road and south of Earl Armstrong Road and will service the Riverside South community within an expansive area zoned for commercial and retail purposes.  It will be one of the only stations to feature a public washroom.\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" |Airport branch\n|-\n|Uplands\n|Will be built East of Uplands Drive next to the EY Centre and will feature two platforms.  It will be the location of the only passing loop on the spur.\n|-\n|{{octs|Airport}}\n|Will be located at the [[Ottawa Macdonald\u2013Cartier International Airport]] and built into the renovated terminal at the departures level.\n|}\n\n==Fleet==\n<!--Other articles link to this section name. Thus, if you change this name, you must code an {{anchor}} for the old section name to avoid broken links.-->\n[[File:Interior of O-Train Alstom Coradia LINT.jpg|thumb|right|Interior of Alstom Coradia LINT]]\nThe Trillium Line initially used three Bombardier Talent [[diesel multiple unit]] (DMU) trains for service. Each train (numbered C1\u2013C3)<ref name=\"sold\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.govdeals.com/index.cfm?fa=Main.Item&itemid=97&acctid=6620|title=Lot of Three (3) 1999 Bombardier Talent Trainsets and Parts - govdeals.com|website=www.govdeals.com|language=en|access-date=2019-01-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013324/https://www.govdeals.com/index.cfm?fa=Main.Item&itemid=97&acctid=6620|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> consisted of three cars, with the front and rear powered and the centre towed. The trains were originally ordered by [[Deutsche Bahn]] and later delivered to OC Transpo. After being retired in 2015, the units were put up for auction multiple times<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-unloading-bombardier-trains-the-original-trillium-line-workhorses|title=City auctioning off Bombardier trains|work=Ottawa Citizen|last=Willing|first=Jon|date=2016-12-28|language=en|access-date=2019-02-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201065328/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/city-unloading-bombardier-trains-the-original-trillium-line-workhorses|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> before eventually being sold for [[Canadian dollar|C$]]25,200 on December 14, 2018.<ref name=\"sold\" />\n\nIn September 2011, [[Alstom]] announced that it would deliver six new two-car [[Alstom Coradia LINT|Coradia LINT]] train sets in 2013;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2011/9/oc-transpo-chooses-alstom-supply-six-new-commuter-trains-Ottawa/|title=OC Transpo chooses Alstom to supply six new commuter trains to Ottawa|date=2011-09-16|publisher=Alstom|accessdate=2012-07-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121117034016/http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2011/9/oc-transpo-chooses-alstom-supply-six-new-commuter-trains-Ottawa/|archive-date=November 17, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> the trains were handed over to OC Transpo in June 2013.<ref name=\"alstom_train_hand_over\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2013/6/in-ottawa-alstom-introduces-first-european-style-commuter-trains-for-north-america/|title=In Ottawa, Alstom introduces first European-style commuter trains for North America|date=2013-06-25|publisher=[[Alstom]]|accessdate=2013-07-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816170114/http://www.alstom.com/press-centre/2013/6/in-ottawa-alstom-introduces-first-european-style-commuter-trains-for-north-america/|archive-date=August 16, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> These trains were put into service on March 2, 2015, and the Bombardier Talent units were subsequently retired.<ref name=\"ottawacitizen.com\">{{Cite web |url=https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/expanded-o-train-service-to-begin-on-monday |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190327172415/https://ottawacitizen.com/news/local-news/expanded-o-train-service-to-begin-on-monday |archive-date=March 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Class\n!Image\n!Type\n!Number of doors\n!Top speed\n!Number\n!Routes operated\n!Built\n!Years of service\n|-\n|[[Bombardier Talent]]&nbsp;BR643\n|[[File:O-Train C3 at Walkley Yard.jpg|frameless|upright=0.8]]\n|[[Diesel multiple unit|DMU]]\n|3 per side\n|{{convert|100|km/h||abbr=on}}\n|{{nowrap|3 \u00d7 3 car units}}<br />(9 cars total)\n| Bayview\u2013Greenboro\n| 2001\n|2001\u20132015\n|-\n|[[Alstom Coradia LINT#LINT 41|Alstom Coradia LINT&nbsp;41]]\n|[[File:J95729 OnOCTotrain 20160815-113119.58 Bayview.jpg|frameless|upright=0.8]]\n|[[Diesel multiple unit|DMU]]\n|2 per side\n|{{convert|140|km/h||abbr=on}}\n|{{nowrap|6 \u00d7 2 pair units}} <br />(12 cars total)\n|Bayview\u2013Greenboro,<br />''South Keys\u2013Airport'' (future)\n|2013\n|2015\u2013present\n|}\n\n=== Future fleet ===\nOn May 3, 2018, it was announced that the city would be purchasing seven new [[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] FLIRT trains to use on the extended Trillium Line after the completion of Stage 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/news/city-secures-funding-to-extend-o-train-trillium-line-to-the-heart-of-riverside-south/|title=City secures funding to extend O-Train Trillium Line to the heart of Riverside South|date=2018-05-10|website=stage2lrt.ca|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190815224841/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/news/city-secures-funding-to-extend-o-train-trillium-line-to-the-heart-of-riverside-south/|archive-date=August 15, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> These trains will be approximately {{convert|80|m|ft|0}} long which is double the {{convert|41|m|ft|0|adj=on}} length of the current Coradia LINT trains. The new trains will operate alongside coupled pairs of the existing LINT trains on the main line as part of a mixed fleet. These vehicles will be manufactured in Switzerland before being transported to Canada for final assembly.<ref>{{Cite techreport|title=Report to: Council|page=52|date=22 February 2019|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Contract-Award-of-Ottawa%E2%80%99s-Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Projects-and-Related-Matters.pdf|accessdate=February 26, 2019|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190226172820/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/Contract-Award-of-Ottawa%E2%80%99s-Stage-2-Light-Rail-Transit-Projects-and-Related-Matters.pdf|archivedate=February 26, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Class\n!Type\n!Number of doors\n!Top speed\n!Number\n!Routes operated\n!Entering service\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Stadler FLIRT|Stadler FLIRT3]]\n|[[Diesel multiple unit#Diesel\u2013electric|DEMU]]\n|8 per side\n|{{Convert|130|km/h||abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://documents.ottawa.ca/sites/default/files/Appendix%20C%20_Natural_and_Air_Quality_TRI_Provincial_EA_Addendum_Appendices.pdf#page=105|title=Appendix C \u2013 Trillium Line EA Addendum Supplementary Terrestrial Information (Ellwood Diamond, Walkley Yard, Bowesville and Limebank) Air Quality Report|access-date=September 18, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918091143/https://documents.ottawa.ca/sites/default/files/Appendix%20C%20_Natural_and_Air_Quality_TRI_Provincial_EA_Addendum_Appendices.pdf#page=105|archive-date=September 18, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|7 x 4 car units<br />(28 cars total, not including power packs)\n|Bayview\u2013Limebank (Stage 2)\n|2022\n|Announced on May 3, 2018. Will have a diesel-electric drive with the possibility of future electrification.\n|}\n\n==Facilities==\nTrain sets are stored at the [[Walkley Yard (OC Transpo)|Walkley Yard]] located northeast of the Greenboro station. Before their retirement, the Bombardier Talent trainsets were maintained by [[Bombardier Transportation]] at the Walkley facilities. Bombardier continues to perform maintenance of the Trillium Line fleet, which included standstill maintenance of the retired Bombardier Talent trains until March 8, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govdeals.com/index.cfm?fa=Main.Item&itemid=97&acctid=6620|title=Lot of Three (3) 1999 Bombardier Talent Trainsets and Parts - govdeals.com|website=www.govdeals.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201013324/https://www.govdeals.com/index.cfm?fa=Main.Item&itemid=97&acctid=6620|archive-date=February 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Walkley Yard was built in 1955 by the [[National Capital Commission]] for the [[Canadian National Railways]] and later sold to the [[Canadian Pacific Railway]]. The yard has enclosed buildings for repairs and outdoor storage tracks.\n\n=== Stage 2 replacement ===\nAs part of the Stage 2 project, a new maintenance facility will be built adjacent and to the west of the existing facilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Appendix7.pdf|title=Relocated Walkley Yard MSF, West of Albion Road|date=2016-01-17|access-date=2019-02-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223020424/https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2017/02/Appendix7.pdf|archive-date=February 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The construction of the new yard facilities began in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ottwatch.ca/meetings/file/627775#page=12|title=Transit Services 2020 Business Plan|last=|first=|date=2019-02-19|website=ottwatch.ca|page=12|url-status=live|access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* [[Confederation Line]]\n* [[Letsgomoose]]\n* [[Light rail in Canada]]\n* [[Light rail in North America]]\n* [[List of tram and light rail transit systems#North America|List of tram and light rail transit systems]]\n* [[Prince of Wales Bridge (Canada)#Future|Prince of Wales Bridge]]\n* [[Rapibus#OC Transpo network connection|Rapibus]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n* [http://www.octranspo.com/routes/o-train-trillium-line OC Transpo \u2013 O-Train Trillium Line (official site)]\n*[http://www.stage2lrt.ca/where/south/ Stage 2 - Trillium Line South] - A City of Ottawa site publicizing O-Train expansion proposals\n**[https://www.stage2lrt.ca/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/lrt_stage2_south_en.png Map of expansion plan]\n* [http://www.ottawa.ca/calendar/ottawa/citycouncil/ttc/2002/12-04/ACS2002-TUP-TRN-0012.htm O-Train Evaluation Report]\n* [http://www.tc.gc.ca/programs/environment/UTSP/otrainlightrailproject.htm O-Train Light Rail Project Summary (Transport Canada)]\n* [http://esteemfoundation.org/emdx//rail/Talent/ O-Train construction pictures]\n*[https://churcher.crcml.org/candate/Otrain.htm Salient Features of the O TRAIN (Trillium) Route]\n\n{{OC Transpo}}\n\n[[Category:O-Train]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2001]]\n[[Category:Railway lines in Canada]]\n[[Category:Light rail in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Blaixx", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:infobox syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trillium_Line"}
{"title_page": "Colorado House career of Douglas Bruce", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\nThe [[Colorado House of Representatives]] career of [[Douglas Bruce]] began with Bruce's appointment to a vacant legislative seat in November 2007 and his swearing-in in January 2008; he was a focal point of controversy during his one term in the state house, becoming the first legislator in Colorado history to be officially censured. He was defeated in the Republican primary in his 2008 bid for a full term.\n\n==2007 House appointment==\nIn October 2007, Bruce announced his plans to seek a seat in the [[Colorado House of Representatives]]. After Rep. [[Bill Cadman]] was appointed to fill a Senate seat vacated by [[Ron May (Colorado legislator)|Ron May]], Bruce sought to be appointed to Cadman's seat representing House District 15.<ref name=\"looking\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=A confident Bruce says he will seek appointment to house seat |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_28797___article.html/seat_county.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=October 23, 2007 |accessdate=November 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026014616/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_28797___article.html/seat_county.html |archivedate=October 26, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"opens\">{{cite news |first=Tom |last=McGhee |title=Senate move opens House to TABOR author |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_28797___article.html/seat_county.html |work=Denver Post |date=November 4, 2007 |accessdate=November 11, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026014616/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_28797___article.html/seat_county.html |archivedate=October 26, 2007 }}</ref> Bruce faced two other Republican challengers for the appointment during a short but contentious battle for the vacancy committee nomination, during which he questioned the professional credentials of one of his opponents, and opponents charged that he was too divisive a figure to successfully represent the district. Ultimately, Bruce received two-thirds of the votes from the 66 members of the vacancy committee, beating out former school board candidate and engineer Reginald Perry and businessman Steve Hasbrouck.<ref name=\"wins\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=GOP chooses Bruce to fill House seat |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_30390___article_pluck.html/seat_vacancy.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=December 3, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071203181453/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_30390___article_pluck.html/seat_vacancy.html |archivedate=December 3, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==2008 legislative session==\n\n===Swearing-in controversy===\n\nBruce postponed being sworn in until January 14, 2008&mdash;several days after the start of the legislative session&mdash;in order to be eligible to serve a full four terms beyond the partial term under Colorado's [[term limits]] rules. The move was criticized by former Republican Senator Ron May and Democratic House Speaker [[Andrew Romanoff]],<ref name=\"late\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Douglas Bruce plans a late start in house |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_30507___article.html/jan_seat.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=December 5, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524014053/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_30507___article.html/jan_seat.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 }}</ref> who, in response to Bruce's actions, called for legislation requiring that newly appointed legislators be sworn in within a specific period of time.<ref name=\"newlaw\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce\u2019s late show may inspire new law |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_31059___article.html/romanoff_house.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=December 19, 2007 |accessdate=December 19, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071222234746/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_31059___article.html/romanoff_house.html |archive-date=December 22, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Such a bill, which would require appointed legislators to be sworn in within 14 days of their selection, was introduced later in the session by Democratic Reps. [[Paul Weissmann]] and [[Dorothy Butcher]];<ref name=\"swearingbill\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=Bill aims to head off Bruce-like late shows |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/state_33394___article.html/weissmann_bill.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=February 22, 2008 |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080328090655/http://www.gazette.com/articles/state_33394___article.html/weissmann_bill.html |archivedate=March 28, 2008 }}</ref> Bruce took the unusual step for a legislator of testifying against the bill at a committee hearing,<ref name=\"tread\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Bruce: Don't tread on me |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_8483164\n|work=Denver Post |date=March 7, 2008 |accessdate=March 7, 2008 }}</ref> but the bill passed the state house, with Bruce casting the only dissenting vote.<ref name=\"takeoff\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=House OKs bill requiring legislators to take office within 14 days |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bill_35093___article.html/bruce_law.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=April 9, 2008 |accessdate=April 11, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411055622/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bill_35093___article.html/bruce_law.html |archivedate=April 11, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nBruce clashed with legislative leaders over the time of his swearing-in, demanding to be sworn in at 10 a.m. in front of the full house. Both Speaker Romanoff and Republican leader [[Mike May (Colorado politician)|Mike May]] requested that Bruce take the oath at a different time, as is customary for vacancy appointments, in order not to interfere with House business.<ref name=\"disrupt\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce wants things his way |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/house_31855___article.html/bruce_romanoff.html |work=The Colorado Springs Gazette |date=January 12, 2008 |accessdate=January 12, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115085415/http://www.gazette.com/articles/house_31855___article.html/bruce_romanoff.html |archivedate=January 15, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"demands\">{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Gathright |title=Bruce demands audience for oath |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jan/12/bruce-demands-audience-for-oath/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=January 12, 2008 |accessdate=January 12, 2008 }}</ref> Bruce was present at the 10 a.m. start of legislative business on January 14, but he was not officially recognized by Speaker Romanoff during the morning session. After House Republicans voted 22-1 to call for a representative to be named for District 15 if Bruce did not take the oath of office by the end of the day, Bruce was sworn in by Romanoff at 1:30&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"kicking\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge |author2=Alan Gathright |title=Bruce alive and kicking in House |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jan/14/bruce-kicks-photographer/ \n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=January 14, 2008 |accessdate=January 14, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAlready fined for an unexcused absence from the commission meeting on Monday morning, Bruce submitted his resignation as an [[El Paso County, Colorado|El Paso County]] Commissioner after being sworn in as a state representative, effective January 15.<ref name=\"foot\">{{cite news |first=Jennier |last=Brown |title=Kick helps get Bruce off on wrong foot with colleagues |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_7972150\n|work=Denver Post |date=January 15, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2008 }}</ref> After his resignation, Bruce sent a letter to the vacancy committee members who would choose his replacement criticizing Amy Lathen, the leading candidate for his commission seat,<ref name=\"lathen\">\n{{cite news |first=Carlyn Ray |last=Mitchell |title=GOP insiders say Lathen has edge |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/county_32070___article.html/lathen_seat.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=January 18, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120153109/http://www.gazette.com/articles/county_32070___article.html/lathen_seat.html |archive-date=January 20, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}\n</ref> as unqualified and inconsistent on tax issues, calling her a \"[[Republican in Name Only]];\" the letter was denounced by El Paso County Republican Party officials.<ref name=\"riles\">{{cite news |first=Carlyn Ray |last=Mitchell |title=Bruce riles GOP again, this time with a letter |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_32082___article.html/letter_lathen.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=January 18, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121181719/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_32082___article.html/letter_lathen.html |archive-date=January 21, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Lathen, who had planned for months to run a primary campaign for the commission seat against Bruce, was elected by the vacancy committee with a majority of votes on the first ballot.<ref name=\"lathen2\">{{cite news |first=R. Scott |last=Rappold |title=Lathen promises a different tone |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/lathen_32163___article.html/county_bruce.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=January 20, 2008 |accessdate=January 20, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123172646/http://www.gazette.com/articles/lathen_32163___article.html/county_bruce.html |archivedate=January 23, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Censure===\nOn the morning before he was sworn in, Bruce was present on the house floor during the session's morning prayer. Javier Manzano, a ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'' photographer, took Bruce's picture during the prayer; Bruce kicked him in the knee, telling Manzano, \"Do not do that again.\" Bruce later accused the photographer of \"violating the order and decorum\" of the house and refused to apologize. Republican Minority Leader Mike May issued a formal apology to the photographer, and state Republican chairman [[Dick Wadhams]] \"strongly denounce[d]\" Bruce's actions.<ref name=\"kicksup\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge |title=House kicks up an investigation |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jan/15/this-isnt-over-leader-may-says/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=January 15, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nSpeaker Romanoff and Minority Leader May convened a bipartisan six-member panel to investigate and made recommendations concerning the incident;<ref name=\"panel\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=House panel steps into kicking incident |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_7980951\n|work=Denver Post |date=January 16, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2008 }}</ref> on Friday, January 18, the panel recommended 6-0 that Bruce be censured by the House for his actions, and 5-1 that a formal apology be requested from Bruce.<ref name=\"chides\">\n{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=House panel chides Bruce over kick |url=http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8010233?_requestid=1919337 |work=Denver Post |date=January 18, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605092158/http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8010233?_requestid=1919337 |archive-date=June 5, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}\n</ref>  Although Manzano testified before the panel, he declined to press criminal charges against Bruce.\n\nRomanoff elected to pursue the censure recommendation, and, on January 24, the full House of Representatives voted 62-1 (with only Rep. [[Kevin Lundberg]] opposed) to censure Bruce. He became the first representative in the recorded history of the state house to be formally censured.<ref name=\"censure\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=House censures Douglas Bruce |url=http://www.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8066076\n|work=Denver Post |date=January 24, 2008 |accessdate=January 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Legislative agenda===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Bruce\n|Year=2008\n|Bill Number 1=HB08-1145\n|Bill Number 2=HB08-1245\n|Bill Number 3=HB08-1277\n|Bill Number 4=HB08-1279\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/9D0E81896FDAB9DE872573AA00569BFB?Open&file=1145_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/A8DBA94A11400B4B872573A80077EEFC?Open&file=1245_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/60B8D8BE5FF1FD85872573D1006D24D2?Open&file=1277_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/D51924CD12A8D744872573D100562AEE?Open&file=1279_01.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning education on fundamental civic documents.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning required reductions in specified government-imposed means of raising revenue.\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning the prohibition of improper uses of property to enforce collections.\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning governmental land use regulations [...]\n}}\n\nFor the 2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, Bruce was named to seats on the House Finance Committee and the House State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee.<ref name=\"cmte2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=January 19, 2008 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref> At the start of the 2008 General Assembly session, before being sworn in, Bruce announced his opposition to a large portion of the House Republican caucus legislative agenda, including a [[sales tax holiday]] for school supplies, a [[pine beetle]] mitigation fund, new specialty [[license plates]], and targeted [[tax credits]], noting in a letter to Republican [[whip]] [[Cory Gardner]]: \"I thought the GOP was the party of less government and more freedom, of protecting individualism, not streamlining socialism.\"<ref name=\"nonono\">{{cite news |first=Cara |last=DeGette |title=Douglas Bruce's Message To His Party: No! No! No! |url=http://www.coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=3322 |work=Colorado Confidential |date=January 11, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe first bill introduced by Bruce during the 2008 session was a measure to require the Colorado Department of Education to distribute copies of the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]] and [[U.S. Constitution]] to high school seniors, to mandate classroom instruction on the documents,<ref name=\"declar\">\n{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Assembly Glance: Thursday in review |url=http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8010233?_requestid=1919337 |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=January 18, 2008 |accessdate=January 19, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605092158/http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8010233?_requestid=1919337 |archive-date=June 5, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}l\n</ref> and to offer a brief [[constitutional law]] course to members of the [[Colorado General Assembly]].<ref name=\"school\">{{cite news|first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Bruce wants colleagues schooled |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/01/20/012108_3A_Bruce_bill.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=January 20, 2008 |accessdate=January 23, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The bill died after facing unanimous opposition from the House Education Committee.<ref name=\"glance\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |author2=Ed Sealover |title=Assembly glance |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bill_32621___article.html/house_state.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=February 1, 2008 |accessdate=February 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524010947/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bill_32621___article.html/house_state.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAnother of Bruce's bills, which would have prohibited counties from assessing any charges other than property taxes, including fines for delinquent payments or stormwater fees, on property tax bills, was also killed in committee.<ref name=\"tuesday\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |author2=Michael Davidson |title=Tuesday in the General Assembly |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/tax_33336___article.html/colorado_bruce.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=February 19, 2008 |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524014148/http://www.gazette.com/articles/tax_33336___article.html/colorado_bruce.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 }}</ref> Bruce also advanced a measure which would have eliminated ''[[per diem]]'' expense payments for legislators and indexed legislators' pay to inflation, as well as requiring voter approval for any pay increases above this amount.<ref name=\"limit\">{{cite news|author=Associated Press |title=Colo. Plan Would Limit Lawmaker Pay |url=http://www.portfolio.com/news-markets/national-news/ap/2008/02/22/colo-plan-would-limit-lawmaker-pay |work=Conde Nast Portfolio.com |date=February 22, 2008 |accessdate=February 23, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> All four bills introduced by Bruce were killed in committee.<ref name=\"pariah\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Douglas Bruce: A pariah or a beleaguered reformer? |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33745___article.html/committee_waller.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=March 1, 2008 |accessdate=March 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304005655/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33745___article.html/committee_waller.html |archivedate=March 4, 2008 }}</ref> Late in the legislative session, Bruce introduced a bill to create a seven-member bipartisan panel, including three unaffiliated voters, to draw up Colorado's congressional and legislative districts following the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] and [[reapportionment]].<ref name=\"bills2\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=2 bills seek to change how Colorado's electoral districts are drawn |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/gordon_34721___article.html/party_voters.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=March 28, 2008 |accessdate=March 29, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401004337/http://www.gazette.com/articles/gordon_34721___article.html/party_voters.html |archivedate=April 1, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nBruce has also objected to the practice of attaching a \"safety clause\" to bills, a provision which uses a declaration that the bill is \"necessary for the immediate preservation of the public peace, health or safety\" to change the date of enactment and prohibit challenges to the legislation via the petition process. He has pledged to vote against all legislation containing an unjustified safety clause,<ref name=\"safety\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Bruce rips legislation's \"safety clause.\" |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_7981831\n|work=Denver Post |date=January 16, 2008 |accessdate=February 15, 2008 }}</ref> and has offered amendments to a number of bills to remove the safety clause.<ref name=\"venerable\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Venerable \"safety clause\" an early Bruce target |url=http://daily.gazette.com/Repository/ml.asp?Ref=VGhlR2F6ZXR0ZS8yMDA4LzAxLzE2I0FyMDA4MDI=&Mode=HTML&Locale=english-skin-custom\n|work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=January 16, 2008 |accessdate=February 15, 2008 }}</ref> Bruce's amendments often failed on account of legislators' personal hostility towards him; on at least one occasion, after the house voted down his proposal to strike the safety clause, the motion passed after being introduced by another legislator.<ref name=\"pariah\"/> House members eventually developed the practice of supporting the removal of the safety clause if the legislator sponsoring the bill agreed; in 2008, 41% of bill passed had no safety clause, up from 25% the previous year.<ref name=\"smallchange\">{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=Bruce wins small changes on \"safety clause\" |url=http://durangoherald.com/asp-bin/article_generation.asp?article_type=news&article_path=/news/08/news080628_6.htm |work=Durango Herald |date=June 28, 2008 |accessdate=July 20, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nBruce also proposed several changes to House operations and procedure, including use of [[taser]]s by state capitol security&mdash;a proposal received favorably by legislative leaders<ref name=\"taser\">\n{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce plan for Tasers welcomed; request for bigger office isn't |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_34140___article.html/office_capitol.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=March 12, 2008 |accessdate=March 17, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314155820/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_34140___article.html/office_capitol.html |archive-date=March 14, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}\n</ref>&mdash;and increased office space for legislators&mdash;an idea not well received.<ref name=\"offspace\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Roll call, March 13 |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/mar/13/roll-call-march-13/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=March 13, 2008 |accessdate=March 17, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nBruce was a vocal critic of the proposed state budget debated during the 2008 legislative session,<ref name=\"rollcalldom\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Roll call, March 27 |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/mar/27/roll-call-march-27/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=March 27, 2008 |accessdate=March 28, 2008 }}</ref> characterizing the budget's $3,500 in expenditures per Colorado resident as \"fiscal child abuse.\"<ref name=\"passes\">{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=State\u2019s $17.6B budget passes House |url=http://durangoherald.com/asp-bin/article_generation.asp?article_type=news&article_path=/news/08/news080328_1.htm |work=Durango Herald |date=March 28, 2008 |accessdate=March 28, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"child\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=GOP rolls eyes as House Dems cite kids in budget nod |url=http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_8723241 |work=Denver Post |date=March 28, 2008 |accessdate=March 28, 2008 }}</ref> During budget debates, Bruce offered unsuccessful amendments to eliminate 524 new employees at colleges and universities, to cut a federally funded program for prevention of [[sexually transmitted diseases]],<ref name=\"brucecut\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=House Dems thwart GOP efforts to pare down state budget |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/state_34631___article.html/budget_workers.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=March 26, 2008 |accessdate=March 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080328162739/http://www.gazette.com/articles/state_34631___article.html/budget_workers.html |archivedate=March 28, 2008 }}</ref> and to prevent the transfer of 165 contract corrections employees to state payrolls.<ref name=\"takesup\">{{cite news |first=Jane |last=Slater |title=House Takes Up State's Budget |url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/15714444/detail.html |work=TheDenverChannel.com |date=March 26, 2008 |accessdate=March 28, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606133130/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/15714444/detail.html |archive-date=June 6, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBruce also joined with left-leaning and environmental groups in opposing proposed changes to Colorado's petition process that would raise signature requirements and make it more difficult to put proposals to amend the Colorado state constitution on the statewide ballot.<ref name=\"tougher\">{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=Panel: Make it tougher to amend constitution |url=http://durangoherald.com/asp-bin/article_generation.asp?article_type=news&article_path=/news/08/news080410_7.htm |work=Durango Herald |date=April 10, 2008 |accessdate=April 11, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"libbruce\">{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=Liberal groups, Bruce join forces |url=http://durangoherald.com/asp-bin/article_generation.asp?article_type=news&article_path=/news/08/news080502_4.htm |work=Durango Herald |date=May 2, 2008 |accessdate=May 2, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nBruce also entered into debate on, and voted against, a bill to impose new requirements on [[landlord]]s and set standards for rental properties. His actions generated criticism from other legislators, who argued that Bruce should have recused himself from voting on the measure because his ownership of rental properties created a [[conflict of interest]]; two other legislators recused themselves for similar reasons.<ref name=\"tenant\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Hoover |title=House gives initial OK to bill on tenant rights |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9031511 |work=Denver Post |date=April 24, 2008 |accessdate=April 24, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"defendst\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Bruce Defends Voting On Landlord-Tenant Bill |url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/15983568/detail.html |work=TheDenverChannel.com |date=April 24, 2008 |accessdate=April 24, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429161721/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/15983568/detail.html |archive-date=April 29, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Removal from committee===\nOn February 13, Bruce, alone among 100 state legislators, refused to sign on as a cosponsor to an annual joint resolution recognizing [[Military and Veterans Appreciation Day]]. Bruce had protested other resolutions in the legislature as a waste of time,<ref name=\"snubs\">{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Gathright |author2=Daniel J. Chacon |title=Bruce snubs military tribute |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/feb/13/bruce-votes-no-vets/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=February 15, 2008 }}</ref> similar to his practice of refusing to vote on resolutions as an El Paso County commissioner.<ref name=\"riles2\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce riles GOP over veterans resolution |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33094___article.html/veterans_resolution.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=February 14, 2008 |accessdate=February 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220001908/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33094___article.html/veterans_resolution.html |archivedate=February 20, 2008 }}</ref> Later in the session, Bruce proposed a change to House rules to allow members to abstain from voting on resolutions.<ref name=\"view2\">\n{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Our View - Friday |url=http://www.gazette.com/opinion/tax_34208___article.html/increase_colorado.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=March 13, 2008 |accessdate=March 17, 2008 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\nIn response to public complaints, Republican Minority Leader Mike May removed Bruce from the House State, Veterans and Military Affairs Committee, which oversees veterans' issues. Bruce dismissed the move as \"political posturing.\"<ref name=\"tossed\">{{cite news |first=Daniel J. |last=Chacon |title=Rep. Bruce tossed off panel |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/feb/15/bruce-tossed-panel/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=February 15, 2008 |accessdate=February 15, 2008 }}</ref> Other Republican legislators denounced Bruce in a public letter for \"callous indifference\" towards veterans.<ref name=\"honor\">{{cite news|first=Marshall |last=Zelinger |title=Rep. Doug Bruce Refuses To Honor Military |url=http://www.krdo.com/Global/story.asp?S=7870154 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220063051/http://www.krdo.com/Global/story.asp?S=7870154 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 20, 2016 |work=KRDO.com |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=February 15, 2008 }}</ref> Bruce offered as evidence of his support for veterans his successful amendment to a house bill to include interest in a state repayment to the Colorado Veterans Trust Fund, a move which resulted in an additional $636,000 repaid to the fund.<ref name=\"yanked\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |author2=Michael Davidson |title=Bruce yanked off veterans committee |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33171___article.html/veterans_committee.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=February 15, 2008 |accessdate=February 15, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219191627/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33171___article.html/veterans_committee.html |archivedate=February 19, 2008 }}</ref> Bruce would later cite this as one of his major accomplishments during the 2008 session.<ref name=\"pariah\"/>\n\nThe following week, Bruce signed on as a cosponsor to an annual resolution calling for civility between members of the legislature; he said that it did not violate his standard of refusing to support symbolic resolutions because he considered the measure to be a \"pledge of personal behavior.\"<ref name=\"civil\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports | title=House resolves to be civil, Bruce votes aye |url=http://www.denverpost.com/lacrosse/ci_8304878\n|work=Denver Post |date=February 19, 2008 |accessdate=February 23, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Per diem controversy===\nAs a legislator, Bruce was entitled to apply for ''[[per diem]]'' compensation for living expenses during the legislative session. After having delayed his swearing into the state house for five days after the start of the session, Bruce applied for and received compensation for those days amounting to $750 more than what he was legally entitled to. Colorado legislative council staff later accepted responsibility for what was referred to as a \"clerical error\"<ref name=\"perk\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender | title=It's all in a day's perk: wrangling over per diems |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_8318937\n|work=Denver Post |date=February 22, 2008 |accessdate=February 23, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"overch\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge | title=Douglas Bruce overcharges state on per diem |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/feb/20/douglas-bruce-overcharges-state-diem/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=February 20, 2008 |accessdate=February 23, 2008 }}</ref> and has pledged to return the excess funds.<ref name=\"return\">{{cite news |author=Associated Press |title=Douglas Bruce claims too much in expenses, says he'll return money |url=http://www.greeleytrib.com/article/20080221/NEWS/271451441\n|work=Greeley Tribune |date=February 21, 2008 |accessdate=March 1, 2008 }}</ref>\nBruce has pledged to donate his legislative salary and ''per diem'' payments to the non-profit charity \"Active Citizens Together,\"<ref name=\"act\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge | title=Bruce: $750 overcharge an error |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/feb/21/bruce-overcharges-750-cites-error/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=February 21, 2008 |accessdate=February 23, 2008 }}</ref> a group founded by Bruce to educate citizens on personal and property rights<ref name=\"over\">\n{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce asks state for $750 too much |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33361___article.html/days_office.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=February 21, 2008 |accessdate=February 23, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080228025158/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33361___article.html/days_office.html |archive-date=February 28, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}\n</ref> and advocate for limited government.<ref name=\"irony\">{{cite news |first=Cara |last=DeGette |title=The Irony Of The Bruce Anti-Tax Machine |url=http://www.coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=3484 |work=Colorado Confidential |date=February 23, 2008 |accessdate=March 1, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918153035/http://coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=3484 |archive-date=September 18, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===\"Illiterate peasants\" comments===\nOn April 21, 2008, Bruce voiced opposition during house debate on a bill sponsored by Rep. [[Marsha Looper]] to create a [[guest worker program]] to facilitate temporary employment visas for agricultural workers from Mexico. After speaking against [[illegal immigration]] and being advised to restrict comments to the bill by debate chair Rep. [[Kathleen Curry]], Bruce took the floor a second time and commented:\n{{quote|I would like to have the opportunity to state at the microphone why I don't think we need 5,000 more illiterate peasants in Colorado.}}\n\nBruce was immediately [[gavel]]led to order by Rep. Curry, who ruled that he would no longer be recognized during debate on the bill.<ref name=\"peasants\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Bruce: Illegal immigrant workers are 'illiterate peasants'\n|url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/apr/21/bruce-mexican-workers-are-illiterate-peasants/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=April 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 21, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"rebukes\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge |author2=Alan Gathright |title=Rebukes envelop Bruce |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/apr/21/bruce-mexican-workers-are-illiterate-peasants/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=April 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 29, 2008 }}</ref> Bruce's comments were denounced by Assistant Majority Leader [[Terrance Carroll]] as violating the \"decorum of the house;\" they were also criticized by Minority Leader Mike May,<ref name=\"farmwork\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=Bruce calls farmworkers 'illiterate peasants' |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/workers_35510___article.html/bruce_rep.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=April 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424122104/http://www.gazette.com/articles/workers_35510___article.html/bruce_rep.html |archivedate=April 24, 2008 }}</ref> the Mexican consulate in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]].<ref name=\"removed\"/> and the [[Anti-Defamation League]].<ref name=\"adl\">{{cite press release | title=ADL Decries Rep. Bruce Comments Calling Foreign Workers 'Illiterate Peasants' | publisher=Anti-Defamation League | date=April 22, 2008 | url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/DiRaB_41/5274_41.htm | accessdate=April 23, 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517045923/http://www.adl.org/PresRele/DiRaB_41/5274_41.htm | archive-date=May 17, 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The following day, the Latino Faith-Based Initiative, and the Democratic Party Latino Initiative both called for Bruce's resignation from the legislature.<ref name=\"resign\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Critics call for Bruce's resignation after remark |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_35551___article.html/colorado_rep.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=April 22, 2008 |accessdate=April 22, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424122048/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_35551___article.html/colorado_rep.html |archive-date=April 24, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nBruce defended his remarks as being factually accurate, citing dictionary definitions of \"illiterate\" and \"peasant\". Legislators briefly considered bringing a formal ethics complaint against him,<ref name=\"removed\">{{cite news |first=Steven K. |last=Paulson |title=Colo. lawmaker removed from podium over Mexicans remark |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gjejGz2ScBlo-Eccugkvp2u9HLZQD906JKB00 |work=Associated Press |date=April 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504235016/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gjejGz2ScBlo-Eccugkvp2u9HLZQD906JKB00 |archivedate=May 4, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"barred\">\n{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=Bruce barred from speaking after 'illiterate' remark |url=http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_9003612 |work=Denver Post |date=April 21, 2008 |accessdate=April 21, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605122839/http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_9003612 |archive-date=June 5, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}\n</ref> but ultimately chose not to. Legislators responded to Bruce's propensity for generating controversy by declaring that they would \"start ignoring him\".<ref name=\"noprobe\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Hoover |title=No ethics probe for Bruce over Mexican comment |url=http://origin.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9014237 |work=Denver Post |date=April 22, 2008 |accessdate=April 22, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080607053757/http://origin.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9014237 |archive-date=June 7, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"wake\">{{cite news |first=Charlie |last=Brennan |title=Threats in Wake of Bruce Controversy |url=http://www.myfoxcolorado.com/myfox/pages/News/Detail?contentId=6379598&version=1&locale=EN-US&layoutCode=TSTY&pageId=3.2.1 |work=MyFoxColorado |date=April 23, 2008 |accessdate=April 26, 2008 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Rep. Curry requested additional law enforcement protection after receiving an influx of threatening messages from opponents of [[illegal immigration]].<ref name=\"threat\">{{cite news|first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Legislator threatened over Bruce incident |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/04/22/042308_1a_Curry.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=April 22, 2008 |accessdate=April 23, 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080527165721/http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/04/22/042308_1a_Curry.html |archivedate=May 27, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Bruce, however, received hundreds of largely positive email messages in response to news coverage of the controversy.<ref name=\"brigade\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Ingold |title=Brigade of Bruce defenders fires e-mail barrage |url=http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_9031798 |work=Denver Post |date=April 24, 2008 |accessdate=April 24, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"glance3\">{{cite news|first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=Legislative glance: Wednesday in Review |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/fallout_35607___article.html/glance_legislative.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=April 24, 2008 |accessdate=April 24, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524015346/http://www.gazette.com/articles/fallout_35607___article.html/glance_legislative.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 }}</ref> The following weekend, Bruce's comments were the target of a local protest in Colorado Springs attended by about 50.<ref name=\"quote\">{{cite news |first=Annette |last=Espinoza |title=Bruce quote sparks protest |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_9068166 |work=Denver Post |date=April 27, 2008 |accessdate=April 27, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"migrant\">{{cite news |first=Terry |last=Jessup |title=Migrant Workers Protest Bruce's 'Peasant' Comments |url=http://cbs4denver.com/local/bruce.migrant.workers.2.706714.html |work=CBS4Denver.com |date=April 27, 2008 |accessdate=April 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506085110/http://cbs4denver.com/local/bruce.migrant.workers.2.706714.html |archivedate=May 6, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nSeveral days later, Bruce submitted an amendment &mdash; facetiously drafted by the \"linguistic sensitivity codification commission\" &mdash; to another bill addressing immigration issues to substitute \"undocumented, temporary guest resident\" in place of \"illegal aliens\" in statutory language. The amendment was offered and defeated twice.<ref name=\"pc\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=A new, improved and PC Bruce |url=http://www.politicswest.com/23776/new_improved_and_pc_bruce |work=Denver Post |date=April 25, 2008 |accessdate=April 25, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907002213/http://www.politicswest.com/23776/new_improved_and_pc_bruce |archive-date=September 7, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"sensitive\">{{cite news |first=Jeremy |last=Pelzer |title=Bruce shows his sensitive side |url=http://www.politickerco.com/jeremypelzer/1006/bruce-shows-his-sensitive-side |work=PolitickerCO |date=April 25, 2008 |accessdate=April 25, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513011506/http://www.politickerco.com/jeremypelzer/1006/bruce-shows-his-sensitive-side |archive-date=May 13, 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment complaint===\nOn April 30, Bruce was the subject of a sexual harassment complaint after a female legislative staffer alleged that he made inappropriate verbal comments towards her. After being formally confronted by House Speaker [[Andrew Romanoff]], Bruce was instructed to stay away from the woman who filed the complaint, according to reports by other representatives.<ref name=\"complaint\">{{cite news |first=Lynn |last=Bartels |title=Woman files sexual harassment complaint against embattled Bruce |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/apr/30/female-staffer-lodges-complaint-against-bruce/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=April 30, 2008 |accessdate=April 30, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"files\">{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Schrager |title=Bruce accused of sexually harassing staffer |url=http://www.9news.com/news/top-article.aspx?storyid=90954 |work=9News.com |date=April 30, 2008 |accessdate=April 30, 2008 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"accuses\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=Sources: Staffer accuses Bruce of sex harassment |url=http://www.denverpost.com/commented/ci_9114126?source=commented-news |work=Denver Post |date=May 1, 2008 |accessdate=May 1, 2008 }}</ref> Legislative leaders refused to publicly discuss the complaint,<ref name=\"complaint2\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=Complaint against Rep. Bruce still unclear |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9125801 |work=Denver Post |date=May 2, 2008 |accessdate=May 2, 2008 }}</ref> but Douglas Bruce stated in a radio interview that the incident in question involved only looking and smiling at a woman.<ref name=\"justlook\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Bruce says he \"just looked\" at woman |url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_9136176 |work=Denver Post |date=May 2, 2008 |accessdate=May 3, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAfter both Bruce and the woman involved were interviewed by attorneys,<ref name=\"complaint3\">{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Newsome |title=Bruce cleared of sexual harassment |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_38455___article.html/woman_complaint.html |work=Denver Post |date=July 21, 2008 |accessdate=August 8, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905221108/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_38455___article.html/woman_complaint.html |archive-date=September 5, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Bruce reported in July that the harassment complaint had been dismissed for lack of evidence,<ref name=\"dismissed\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=Harassment complaint dismissed, Bruce says  |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9943785 |work=Denver Post |date=July 21, 2008 |accessdate=August 8, 2008 }}</ref> and suggested that the timing of the investigation's conclusion was politically motivated, coming just weeks before a contested primary race.<ref name=\"conspir\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=State Rep. Bruce smells a conspiracy  |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jul/22/state-rep-bruce-smells-a-conspiracy/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=July 22, 2008 |accessdate=August 8, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==2008 election==\nBruce announced in November 2007 that he would stand in the 2008 general election for the House District 15 seat.<ref name=\"among\">{{cite news\n |first=Julia C. \n |last=Martinez \n |title=Douglas Bruce among three vying for House seat \n |url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/opinion/2007/11/27/douglas-bruce-among-three-vying-for-house-seat/ \n |work=Denver Post \n |date=November 27, 2007 \n |accessdate=November 27, 2007 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080101124849/http://blogs.denverpost.com/opinion/2007/11/27/douglas-bruce-among-three-vying-for-house-seat/ \n |archivedate=January 1, 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> He faces a challenge for the Republican nomination from attorney and [[Iraq War]] veteran Mark Waller.<ref name=\"wins\"/> Following the precedent of his county commission campaign four years earlier, Bruce funded his own campaign, refusing to accept private campaign donations;<ref name=\"polgab\">{{cite news |first=Pam |last=Zubeck |title=POLITIGAB: Bruce says no to dependency |url=http://www.gazette.com/news/parade_37868___article.html/crank_district.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=July 2, 2008 |accessdate=August 5, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524020206/http://www.gazette.com/news/parade_37868___article.html/crank_district.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 }}</ref> instead, Bruce donated over $30,000 of his own money to his campaign.<ref name=\"thous\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=POLITIGAB: Thousands spent in primary runs |url=http://www.gazette.com/news/candidates_39058___article.html/state_primary.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=August 7, 2008 |accessdate=August 10, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110524043205/http://www.gazette.com/news/candidates_39058___article.html/state_primary.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 }}</ref> He did, however, unsuccessfully solicit donations for his charity, Active Citizens Together, from other lawmakers.<ref name=\"strife\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Hoover |title=Bruce's rival says strife fails voters  |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9963889 |work=Denver Post |date=July 22, 2008 |accessdate=August 8, 2008 }}</ref> Reflecting Bruce's status as a \"pariah\" among some Colorado Springs Republicans,<ref name=\"pariah\"/> Waller received endorsements or contributions during his campaign from at least five sitting state representatives, including [[Bob Gardner]],{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} [[Larry Liston]],<ref name=\"pariah\"/> and [[Marsha Looper]],<ref name=\"thous\"/> as well as former Sen. [[Ron May (Colorado legislator)|Ron May]]<ref name=\"trail\">\n{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=On the stump - February 29, 2008 |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/waller_33740___article.html/district_business.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=February 29, 2008 |accessdate=March 2, 2008 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130123215239/http://www.gazette.com/articles/waller_33740___article.html/district_business.html |archive-date=January 23, 2013 |url-status=dead  }}\n</ref> and Colorado Attorney General [[John Suthers]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nWaller outpolled Bruce by receiving 57% of the vote at the Republican assembly in March, claiming the top line on the August Republican primary ballot;<ref name=\"no2\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce knocked to No. 2 on the ballot |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33993___article.html/waller_saturday.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=March 8, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310224207/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33993___article.html/waller_saturday.html |archivedate=March 10, 2008 }}</ref> he was supported by some delegates who had voted for Bruce's legislative appointment months earlier.<ref name=\"werewrong\">{{cite news |first=Cara |last=DeGette |title=Former Douglas Bruce Supporter: 'We Were Wrong' |url=http://coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do;jsessionid=4D722AE30C0FD392D188670110FA2D33?diaryId=3644 |work=Colorado Confidential |date=April 5, 2008 |accessdate=April 22, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080426225334/http://coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do;jsessionid=4D722AE30C0FD392D188670110FA2D33?diaryId=3644 |archive-date=April 26, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"lipsink\"/> During his campaign, Waller did not draw a contrast on political positions with Bruce, but argued that Bruce's temperament caused him to be an ineffective legislator.<ref name=\"toughrace\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Waller has a tough fight in race with Douglas Bruce |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/tough_38171___article.html/waller_bruce.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=July 12, 2007 |accessdate=August 7, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524020508/http://www.gazette.com/articles/tough_38171___article.html/waller_bruce.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nBruce faced criticism from House Democratic and Republican leaders in April for distributing campaign fliers critical of Waller to Republican representatives on the House floor. Although not a violation of the law or House rules, legislative leaders denounced the action as a breach of decorum and tradition.<ref name=\"fire\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce draws fire over fliers |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_34830___article.html/house_fliers.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=April 1, 2008 |accessdate=April 2, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524020632/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_34830___article.html/house_fliers.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"rebuke\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Ingold |author2=Jessica Fender |title=Bruce fliers bring rebuke |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_8774429 |work=Denver Post |date=April 1, 2008 |accessdate=April 2, 2008 }}</ref> Waller also called for Bruce's resignation in April 2008, after Bruce's controversial comments about Mexican guest workers.<ref name=\"noprobe\"/> Bruce, in response, characterised Waller as a \"conformer\" rather than a \"reformer,\" and stated that his controversial actions were designed to draw attention to inappropriate legislative actions.<ref name=\"lipsink\">{{cite news |first=Karen E. |last=Crummy |title=Bruce's lip sinking his ship? |url=http://www.denverpost.com/search/ci_9099564 |work=Denver Post |date=April 30, 2008 |accessdate=April 30, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nShortly before the August primary, Bruce was again criticized by Waller for mailing flyers promoting his charity, Active Citizens Together, soliciting volunteers and donations for the charity and stating: \"to reform government, ACT with Douglas Bruce.\" Although Waller declared that the flyers were \"an obvious attempt at campaigning,\" he did not file a complaint with the [[Colorado Secretary of State]]'s office, as he believed no laws were actually broken; the flyers did not mention any of Bruce's elected positions.<ref name=\"jugular\">{{cite news |first=Pam |last=Zubeck |title=Politigab: Jeff Crank launches another radio ad |url=http://www.gazette.com/news/bruce_38016___article_news.html/waller_act.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=July 8, 2008 |accessdate=August 6, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130124172108/http://www.gazette.com/news/bruce_38016___article_news.html/waller_act.html |archivedate=January 24, 2013 }}</ref> Bruce was also criticized for listing endorsements on his website from political officials who had endorsed his campaign for county commissioner, but not specifically endorsed his legislative campaign. After attention was called to the discrepancy, Bruce had the erroneous endorsements removed, citing an \"overzealous webmaster.\"<ref name=\"sayendor\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Backers named on Bruce Web site say endorsement from 2004  |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jul/21/backers-named-bruce-web-site-say-endorsement-2004/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=July 21, 2008 |accessdate=August 8, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn turn, Bruce filed several campaign finance complaints against Waller, all but one of which&mdash;an accusation that Waller improperly accepted a corporate donation&mdash;were dismissed.<ref name=\"faceoff\"/> The hearing on Bruce's complaint was postponed until after the primary, over Bruce's objection, but resulted in Waller being cited and fined for failing to disclose a campaign contribution.<ref name=\"failing\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Waller campaign fined for failing to report funds |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/waller_40196___article.html/campaign_schuck.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=September 4, 2008 |accessdate=September 6, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606140434/http://www.gazette.com/articles/waller_40196___article.html/campaign_schuck.html |archivedate=June 6, 2012 }}</ref> Bruce also criticized Waller for his failure to vote in several recent elections, including the 2004 general election.<ref name=\"faceoff\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Bruce, Waller face off |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/face_38692___article.html/republican_candidates.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=July 27, 2008 |accessdate=August 8, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524020810/http://www.gazette.com/articles/face_38692___article.html/republican_candidates.html |archivedate=May 24, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nBruce was narrowly defeated for the Republican nomination in the August 12 party primary, taking only 48 percent of the vote to Waller's 52 percent.<ref name=\"defeats\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Waller defeats Bruce |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_39268___article_news.html/waller_republican.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=August 12, 2008 |accessdate=August 13, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130124002040/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_39268___article_news.html/waller_republican.html |archivedate=January 24, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nDemocrat Allison Hunter withdrew from the race in December 2007, arguing that Bruce's appointment by a vacancy committee gave him \"too great an advantage\" in general election;<ref name=\"hunter\">{{cite news |first=Carlyn Ray |last=Mitchell |title=Dem opens bid for commission seat |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/hunter_33631___article.html/county_seat.html\n|work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=February 27, 2008 |accessdate=March 2, 2008 }}</ref> Waller will face Democrat Michelle Maksimowicz in November 2008.<ref name=\"defeats\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Colorado House Career Of Douglas Bruce}}\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives|Bruce, Douglas Colorado House career]]\n[[Category:Tenures in political office by individual|Bruce, Douglas]]\n[[Category:2000s in Colorado]]\n", "text_old": "The [[Colorado House of Representatives]] career of [[Douglas Bruce]] began with Bruce's appointment to a vacant legislative seat in November 2007 and his swearing-in in January 2008; he was a focal point of controversy during his one term in the state house, becoming the first legislator in Colorado history to be officially censured. He was defeated in the Republican primary in his 2008 bid for a full term.\n\n==2007 House appointment==\nIn October 2007, Bruce announced his plans to seek a seat in the [[Colorado House of Representatives]]. After Rep. [[Bill Cadman]] was appointed to fill a Senate seat vacated by [[Ron May (Colorado legislator)|Ron May]], Bruce sought to be appointed to Cadman's seat representing House District 15.<ref name=\"looking\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=A confident Bruce says he will seek appointment to house seat |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_28797___article.html/seat_county.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=October 23, 2007 |accessdate=2007-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026014616/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_28797___article.html/seat_county.html |archivedate=October 26, 2007 }}</ref><ref name=\"opens\">{{cite news |first=Tom |last=McGhee |title=Senate move opens House to TABOR author |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_28797___article.html/seat_county.html |work=Denver Post |date=November 4, 2007 |accessdate=2007-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026014616/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_28797___article.html/seat_county.html |archivedate=October 26, 2007 }}</ref> Bruce faced two other Republican challengers for the appointment during a short but contentious battle for the vacancy committee nomination, during which he questioned the professional credentials of one of his opponents, and opponents charged that he was too divisive a figure to successfully represent the district. Ultimately, Bruce received two-thirds of the votes from the 66 members of the vacancy committee, beating out former school board candidate and engineer Reginald Perry and businessman Steve Hasbrouck.<ref name=\"wins\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=GOP chooses Bruce to fill House seat |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_30390___article_pluck.html/seat_vacancy.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=3 December 2007 |accessdate=2007-12-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071203181453/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_30390___article_pluck.html/seat_vacancy.html |archivedate=3 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\n==2008 legislative session==\n\n===Swearing-in controversy===\n\nBruce postponed being sworn in until January 14, 2008&mdash;several days after the start of the legislative session&mdash;in order to be eligible to serve a full four terms beyond the partial term under Colorado's [[term limits]] rules. The move was criticized by former Republican Senator Ron May and Democratic House Speaker [[Andrew Romanoff]],<ref name=\"late\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Douglas Bruce plans a late start in house |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_30507___article.html/jan_seat.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=5 December 2007 |accessdate=2007-12-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524014053/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_30507___article.html/jan_seat.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 }}</ref> who, in response to Bruce's actions, called for legislation requiring that newly appointed legislators be sworn in within a specific period of time.<ref name=\"newlaw\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce\u2019s late show may inspire new law |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_31059___article.html/romanoff_house.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=19 December 2007 |accessdate=2007-12-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071222234746/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_31059___article.html/romanoff_house.html |archive-date=22 December 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Such a bill, which would require appointed legislators to be sworn in within 14 days of their selection, was introduced later in the session by Democratic Reps. [[Paul Weissmann]] and [[Dorothy Butcher]];<ref name=\"swearingbill\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=Bill aims to head off Bruce-like late shows |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/state_33394___article.html/weissmann_bill.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=22 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080328090655/http://www.gazette.com/articles/state_33394___article.html/weissmann_bill.html |archivedate=28 March 2008 }}</ref> Bruce took the unusual step for a legislator of testifying against the bill at a committee hearing,<ref name=\"tread\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=Bruce: Don't tread on me |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_8483164\n|work=Denver Post |date=7 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-07 }}</ref> but the bill passed the state house, with Bruce casting the only dissenting vote.<ref name=\"takeoff\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=House OKs bill requiring legislators to take office within 14 days |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bill_35093___article.html/bruce_law.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=9 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411055622/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bill_35093___article.html/bruce_law.html |archivedate=11 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nBruce clashed with legislative leaders over the time of his swearing-in, demanding to be sworn in at 10 a.m. in front of the full house. Both Speaker Romanoff and Republican leader [[Mike May (Colorado politician)|Mike May]] requested that Bruce take the oath at a different time, as is customary for vacancy appointments, in order not to interfere with House business.<ref name=\"disrupt\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce wants things his way |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/house_31855___article.html/bruce_romanoff.html |work=The Colorado Springs Gazette |date=12 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080115085415/http://www.gazette.com/articles/house_31855___article.html/bruce_romanoff.html |archivedate=15 January 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"demands\">{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Gathright |title=Bruce demands audience for oath |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jan/12/bruce-demands-audience-for-oath/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=12 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-12 }}</ref> Bruce was present at the 10 a.m. start of legislative business on January 14, but he was not officially recognized by Speaker Romanoff during the morning session. After House Republicans voted 22-1 to call for a representative to be named for District 15 if Bruce did not take the oath of office by the end of the day, Bruce was sworn in by Romanoff at 1:30&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"kicking\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge |author2=Alan Gathright |title=Bruce alive and kicking in House |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jan/14/bruce-kicks-photographer/ \n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=14 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-14 }}</ref>\n\nAlready fined for an unexcused absence from the commission meeting on Monday morning, Bruce submitted his resignation as an [[El Paso County, Colorado|El Paso County]] Commissioner after being sworn in as a state representative, effective January 15.<ref name=\"foot\">{{cite news |first=Jennier |last=Brown |title=Kick helps get Bruce off on wrong foot with colleagues |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_7972150\n|work=Denver Post |date=15 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-19 }}</ref> After his resignation, Bruce sent a letter to the vacancy committee members who would choose his replacement criticizing Amy Lathen, the leading candidate for his commission seat,<ref name=\"lathen\">\n{{cite news |first=Carlyn Ray |last=Mitchell |title=GOP insiders say Lathen has edge |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/county_32070___article.html/lathen_seat.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=18 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120153109/http://www.gazette.com/articles/county_32070___article.html/lathen_seat.html |archive-date=20 January 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> as unqualified and inconsistent on tax issues, calling her a \"[[Republican in Name Only]];\" the letter was denounced by El Paso County Republican Party officials.<ref name=\"riles\">{{cite news |first=Carlyn Ray |last=Mitchell |title=Bruce riles GOP again, this time with a letter |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_32082___article.html/letter_lathen.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=18 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080121181719/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_32082___article.html/letter_lathen.html |archive-date=21 January 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Lathen, who had planned for months to run a primary campaign for the commission seat against Bruce, was elected by the vacancy committee with a majority of votes on the first ballot.<ref name=\"lathen2\">{{cite news |first=R. Scott |last=Rappold |title=Lathen promises a different tone |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/lathen_32163___article.html/county_bruce.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080123172646/http://www.gazette.com/articles/lathen_32163___article.html/county_bruce.html |archivedate=23 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===Censure===\nOn the morning before he was sworn in, Bruce was present on the house floor during the session's morning prayer. Javier Manzano, a ''[[Rocky Mountain News]]'' photographer, took Bruce's picture during the prayer; Bruce kicked him in the knee, telling Manzano, \"Do not do that again.\" Bruce later accused the photographer of \"violating the order and decorum\" of the house and refused to apologize. Republican Minority Leader Mike May issued a formal apology to the photographer, and state Republican chairman [[Dick Wadhams]] \"strongly denounce[d]\" Bruce's actions.<ref name=\"kicksup\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge |title=House kicks up an investigation |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jan/15/this-isnt-over-leader-may-says/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=15 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-19 }}</ref>\n\nSpeaker Romanoff and Minority Leader May convened a bipartisan six-member panel to investigate and made recommendations concerning the incident;<ref name=\"panel\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=House panel steps into kicking incident |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_7980951\n|work=Denver Post |date=16 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-19 }}</ref> on Friday, January 18, the panel recommended 6-0 that Bruce be censured by the House for his actions, and 5-1 that a formal apology be requested from Bruce.<ref name=\"chides\">\n{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Brown |title=House panel chides Bruce over kick |url=http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8010233?_requestid=1919337 |work=Denver Post |date=18 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605092158/http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8010233?_requestid=1919337 |archive-date=5 June 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>  Although Manzano testified before the panel, he declined to press criminal charges against Bruce.\n\nRomanoff elected to pursue the censure recommendation, and, on January 24, the full House of Representatives voted 62-1 (with only Rep. [[Kevin Lundberg]] opposed) to censure Bruce. He became the first representative in the recorded history of the state house to be formally censured.<ref name=\"censure\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=House censures Douglas Bruce |url=http://www.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8066076\n|work=Denver Post |date=24 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-24 }}</ref>\n\n===Legislative agenda===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Bruce\n|Year=2008\n|Bill Number 1=HB08-1145\n|Bill Number 2=HB08-1245\n|Bill Number 3=HB08-1277\n|Bill Number 4=HB08-1279\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/9D0E81896FDAB9DE872573AA00569BFB?Open&file=1145_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/A8DBA94A11400B4B872573A80077EEFC?Open&file=1245_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/60B8D8BE5FF1FD85872573D1006D24D2?Open&file=1277_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/D51924CD12A8D744872573D100562AEE?Open&file=1279_01.pdf\n|Bill Status 1=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 2=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning education on fundamental civic documents.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning required reductions in specified government-imposed means of raising revenue.\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning the prohibition of improper uses of property to enforce collections.\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning governmental land use regulations [...]\n}}\n\nFor the 2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, Bruce was named to seats on the House Finance Committee and the House State, Veterans, and Military Affairs Committee.<ref name=\"cmte2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2008-01-19 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref> At the start of the 2008 General Assembly session, before being sworn in, Bruce announced his opposition to a large portion of the House Republican caucus legislative agenda, including a [[sales tax holiday]] for school supplies, a [[pine beetle]] mitigation fund, new specialty [[license plates]], and targeted [[tax credits]], noting in a letter to Republican [[whip]] [[Cory Gardner]]: \"I thought the GOP was the party of less government and more freedom, of protecting individualism, not streamlining socialism.\"<ref name=\"nonono\">{{cite news |first=Cara |last=DeGette |title=Douglas Bruce's Message To His Party: No! No! No! |url=http://www.coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=3322 |work=Colorado Confidential |date=11 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-19 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe first bill introduced by Bruce during the 2008 session was a measure to require the Colorado Department of Education to distribute copies of the [[United States Declaration of Independence|Declaration of Independence]] and [[U.S. Constitution]] to high school seniors, to mandate classroom instruction on the documents,<ref name=\"declar\">\n{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Assembly Glance: Thursday in review |url=http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8010233?_requestid=1919337 |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=18 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605092158/http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_8010233?_requestid=1919337 |archive-date=5 June 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}l\n</ref> and to offer a brief [[constitutional law]] course to members of the [[Colorado General Assembly]].<ref name=\"school\">{{cite news|first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Bruce wants colleagues schooled |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/01/20/012108_3A_Bruce_bill.html |work=Grand Junction Daily Sentinel |date=20 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-23 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The bill died after facing unanimous opposition from the House Education Committee.<ref name=\"glance\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |author2=Ed Sealover |title=Assembly glance |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bill_32621___article.html/house_state.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=1 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524010947/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bill_32621___article.html/house_state.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAnother of Bruce's bills, which would have prohibited counties from assessing any charges other than property taxes, including fines for delinquent payments or stormwater fees, on property tax bills, was also killed in committee.<ref name=\"tuesday\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |author2=Michael Davidson |title=Tuesday in the General Assembly |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/tax_33336___article.html/colorado_bruce.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=19 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524014148/http://www.gazette.com/articles/tax_33336___article.html/colorado_bruce.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 }}</ref> Bruce also advanced a measure which would have eliminated ''[[per diem]]'' expense payments for legislators and indexed legislators' pay to inflation, as well as requiring voter approval for any pay increases above this amount.<ref name=\"limit\">{{cite news|author=Associated Press |title=Colo. Plan Would Limit Lawmaker Pay |url=http://www.portfolio.com/news-markets/national-news/ap/2008/02/22/colo-plan-would-limit-lawmaker-pay |work=Conde Nast Portfolio.com |date=22 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-23 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> All four bills introduced by Bruce were killed in committee.<ref name=\"pariah\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Douglas Bruce: A pariah or a beleaguered reformer? |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33745___article.html/committee_waller.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=1 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080304005655/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33745___article.html/committee_waller.html |archivedate=4 March 2008 }}</ref> Late in the legislative session, Bruce introduced a bill to create a seven-member bipartisan panel, including three unaffiliated voters, to draw up Colorado's congressional and legislative districts following the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] and [[reapportionment]].<ref name=\"bills2\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=2 bills seek to change how Colorado's electoral districts are drawn |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/gordon_34721___article.html/party_voters.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=28 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401004337/http://www.gazette.com/articles/gordon_34721___article.html/party_voters.html |archivedate=1 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nBruce has also objected to the practice of attaching a \"safety clause\" to bills, a provision which uses a declaration that the bill is \"necessary for the immediate preservation of the public peace, health or safety\" to change the date of enactment and prohibit challenges to the legislation via the petition process. He has pledged to vote against all legislation containing an unjustified safety clause,<ref name=\"safety\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Bruce rips legislation's \"safety clause.\" |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_7981831\n|work=Denver Post |date=16 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-15 }}</ref> and has offered amendments to a number of bills to remove the safety clause.<ref name=\"venerable\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Venerable \"safety clause\" an early Bruce target |url=http://daily.gazette.com/Repository/ml.asp?Ref=VGhlR2F6ZXR0ZS8yMDA4LzAxLzE2I0FyMDA4MDI=&Mode=HTML&Locale=english-skin-custom\n|work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=16 January 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-15 }}</ref> Bruce's amendments often failed on account of legislators' personal hostility towards him; on at least one occasion, after the house voted down his proposal to strike the safety clause, the motion passed after being introduced by another legislator.<ref name=\"pariah\"/> House members eventually developed the practice of supporting the removal of the safety clause if the legislator sponsoring the bill agreed; in 2008, 41% of bill passed had no safety clause, up from 25% the previous year.<ref name=\"smallchange\">{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=Bruce wins small changes on \"safety clause\" |url=http://durangoherald.com/asp-bin/article_generation.asp?article_type=news&article_path=/news/08/news080628_6.htm |work=Durango Herald |date=28 June 2008 |accessdate=2008-07-20 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nBruce also proposed several changes to House operations and procedure, including use of [[taser]]s by state capitol security&mdash;a proposal received favorably by legislative leaders<ref name=\"taser\">\n{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce plan for Tasers welcomed; request for bigger office isn't |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_34140___article.html/office_capitol.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=12 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080314155820/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_34140___article.html/office_capitol.html |archive-date=14 March 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref>&mdash;and increased office space for legislators&mdash;an idea not well received.<ref name=\"offspace\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Roll call, March 13 |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/mar/13/roll-call-march-13/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=13 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-17 }}</ref>\n\nBruce was a vocal critic of the proposed state budget debated during the 2008 legislative session,<ref name=\"rollcalldom\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Roll call, March 27 |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/mar/27/roll-call-march-27/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=27 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28 }}</ref> characterizing the budget's $3,500 in expenditures per Colorado resident as \"fiscal child abuse.\"<ref name=\"passes\">{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=State\u2019s $17.6B budget passes House |url=http://durangoherald.com/asp-bin/article_generation.asp?article_type=news&article_path=/news/08/news080328_1.htm |work=Durango Herald |date=28 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"child\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=GOP rolls eyes as House Dems cite kids in budget nod |url=http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_8723241 |work=Denver Post |date=28 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28 }}</ref> During budget debates, Bruce offered unsuccessful amendments to eliminate 524 new employees at colleges and universities, to cut a federally funded program for prevention of [[sexually transmitted diseases]],<ref name=\"brucecut\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=House Dems thwart GOP efforts to pare down state budget |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/state_34631___article.html/budget_workers.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=26 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080328162739/http://www.gazette.com/articles/state_34631___article.html/budget_workers.html |archivedate=28 March 2008 }}</ref> and to prevent the transfer of 165 contract corrections employees to state payrolls.<ref name=\"takesup\">{{cite news |first=Jane |last=Slater |title=House Takes Up State's Budget |url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/15714444/detail.html |work=TheDenverChannel.com |date=26 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606133130/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/15714444/detail.html |archive-date=6 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBruce also joined with left-leaning and environmental groups in opposing proposed changes to Colorado's petition process that would raise signature requirements and make it more difficult to put proposals to amend the Colorado state constitution on the statewide ballot.<ref name=\"tougher\">{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=Panel: Make it tougher to amend constitution |url=http://durangoherald.com/asp-bin/article_generation.asp?article_type=news&article_path=/news/08/news080410_7.htm |work=Durango Herald |date=10 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-11 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"libbruce\">{{cite news|first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=Liberal groups, Bruce join forces |url=http://durangoherald.com/asp-bin/article_generation.asp?article_type=news&article_path=/news/08/news080502_4.htm |work=Durango Herald |date=2 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-05-02 }}{{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nBruce also entered into debate on, and voted against, a bill to impose new requirements on [[landlord]]s and set standards for rental properties. His actions generated criticism from other legislators, who argued that Bruce should have recused himself from voting on the measure because his ownership of rental properties created a [[conflict of interest]]; two other legislators recused themselves for similar reasons.<ref name=\"tenant\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Hoover |title=House gives initial OK to bill on tenant rights |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9031511 |work=Denver Post |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"defendst\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Bruce Defends Voting On Landlord-Tenant Bill |url=http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/15983568/detail.html |work=TheDenverChannel.com |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080429161721/http://www.thedenverchannel.com/news/15983568/detail.html |archive-date=29 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Removal from committee===\nOn February 13, Bruce, alone among 100 state legislators, refused to sign on as a cosponsor to an annual joint resolution recognizing [[Military and Veterans Appreciation Day]]. Bruce had protested other resolutions in the legislature as a waste of time,<ref name=\"snubs\">{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Gathright |author2=Daniel J. Chacon |title=Bruce snubs military tribute |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/feb/13/bruce-votes-no-vets/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=13 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-15 }}</ref> similar to his practice of refusing to vote on resolutions as an El Paso County commissioner.<ref name=\"riles2\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce riles GOP over veterans resolution |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33094___article.html/veterans_resolution.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=14 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080220001908/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33094___article.html/veterans_resolution.html |archivedate=20 February 2008 }}</ref> Later in the session, Bruce proposed a change to House rules to allow members to abstain from voting on resolutions.<ref name=\"view2\">\n{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Our View - Friday |url=http://www.gazette.com/opinion/tax_34208___article.html/increase_colorado.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=13 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-17 }}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\nIn response to public complaints, Republican Minority Leader Mike May removed Bruce from the House State, Veterans and Military Affairs Committee, which oversees veterans' issues. Bruce dismissed the move as \"political posturing.\"<ref name=\"tossed\">{{cite news |first=Daniel J. |last=Chacon |title=Rep. Bruce tossed off panel |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/feb/15/bruce-tossed-panel/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=15 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-15 }}</ref> Other Republican legislators denounced Bruce in a public letter for \"callous indifference\" towards veterans.<ref name=\"honor\">{{cite news|first=Marshall |last=Zelinger |title=Rep. Doug Bruce Refuses To Honor Military |url=http://www.krdo.com/Global/story.asp?S=7870154 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220063051/http://www.krdo.com/Global/story.asp?S=7870154 |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 December 2016 |work=KRDO.com |date=13 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-15 }}</ref> Bruce offered as evidence of his support for veterans his successful amendment to a house bill to include interest in a state repayment to the Colorado Veterans Trust Fund, a move which resulted in an additional $636,000 repaid to the fund.<ref name=\"yanked\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |author2=Michael Davidson |title=Bruce yanked off veterans committee |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33171___article.html/veterans_committee.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=15 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080219191627/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33171___article.html/veterans_committee.html |archivedate=19 February 2008 }}</ref> Bruce would later cite this as one of his major accomplishments during the 2008 session.<ref name=\"pariah\"/>\n\nThe following week, Bruce signed on as a cosponsor to an annual resolution calling for civility between members of the legislature; he said that it did not violate his standard of refusing to support symbolic resolutions because he considered the measure to be a \"pledge of personal behavior.\"<ref name=\"civil\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports | title=House resolves to be civil, Bruce votes aye |url=http://www.denverpost.com/lacrosse/ci_8304878\n|work=Denver Post |date=19 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-23 }}</ref>\n\n===Per diem controversy===\nAs a legislator, Bruce was entitled to apply for ''[[per diem]]'' compensation for living expenses during the legislative session. After having delayed his swearing into the state house for five days after the start of the session, Bruce applied for and received compensation for those days amounting to $750 more than what he was legally entitled to. Colorado legislative council staff later accepted responsibility for what was referred to as a \"clerical error\"<ref name=\"perk\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender | title=It's all in a day's perk: wrangling over per diems |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_8318937\n|work=Denver Post |date=22 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-23 }}</ref><ref name=\"overch\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge | title=Douglas Bruce overcharges state on per diem |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/feb/20/douglas-bruce-overcharges-state-diem/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=20 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-23 }}</ref> and has pledged to return the excess funds.<ref name=\"return\">{{cite news |author=Associated Press |title=Douglas Bruce claims too much in expenses, says he'll return money |url=http://www.greeleytrib.com/article/20080221/NEWS/271451441\n|work=Greeley Tribune |date=21 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-01 }}</ref>\nBruce has pledged to donate his legislative salary and ''per diem'' payments to the non-profit charity \"Active Citizens Together,\"<ref name=\"act\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge | title=Bruce: $750 overcharge an error |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/feb/21/bruce-overcharges-750-cites-error/\n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=21 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-23 }}</ref> a group founded by Bruce to educate citizens on personal and property rights<ref name=\"over\">\n{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce asks state for $750 too much |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33361___article.html/days_office.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=21 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-23 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080228025158/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33361___article.html/days_office.html |archive-date=28 February 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> and advocate for limited government.<ref name=\"irony\">{{cite news |first=Cara |last=DeGette |title=The Irony Of The Bruce Anti-Tax Machine |url=http://www.coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=3484 |work=Colorado Confidential |date=23 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080918153035/http://coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do?diaryId=3484 |archive-date=18 September 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===\"Illiterate peasants\" comments===\nOn April 21, 2008, Bruce voiced opposition during house debate on a bill sponsored by Rep. [[Marsha Looper]] to create a [[guest worker program]] to facilitate temporary employment visas for agricultural workers from Mexico. After speaking against [[illegal immigration]] and being advised to restrict comments to the bill by debate chair Rep. [[Kathleen Curry]], Bruce took the floor a second time and commented:\n{{quote|I would like to have the opportunity to state at the microphone why I don't think we need 5,000 more illiterate peasants in Colorado.}}\n\nBruce was immediately [[gavel]]led to order by Rep. Curry, who ruled that he would no longer be recognized during debate on the bill.<ref name=\"peasants\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Bruce: Illegal immigrant workers are 'illiterate peasants'\n|url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/apr/21/bruce-mexican-workers-are-illiterate-peasants/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=21 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-21 }}</ref><ref name=\"rebukes\">{{cite news |first=Chris |last=Barge |author2=Alan Gathright |title=Rebukes envelop Bruce |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/apr/21/bruce-mexican-workers-are-illiterate-peasants/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=21 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-29 }}</ref> Bruce's comments were denounced by Assistant Majority Leader [[Terrance Carroll]] as violating the \"decorum of the house;\" they were also criticized by Minority Leader Mike May,<ref name=\"farmwork\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=Bruce calls farmworkers 'illiterate peasants' |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/workers_35510___article.html/bruce_rep.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=21 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424122104/http://www.gazette.com/articles/workers_35510___article.html/bruce_rep.html |archivedate=24 April 2008 }}</ref> the Mexican consulate in [[Denver, Colorado|Denver]].<ref name=\"removed\"/> and the [[Anti-Defamation League]].<ref name=\"adl\">{{cite press release | title=ADL Decries Rep. Bruce Comments Calling Foreign Workers 'Illiterate Peasants' | publisher=Anti-Defamation League | date=22 April 2008 | url=http://www.adl.org/PresRele/DiRaB_41/5274_41.htm | accessdate=2008-04-23 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517045923/http://www.adl.org/PresRele/DiRaB_41/5274_41.htm | archive-date=17 May 2008 | url-status=dead }}</ref> The following day, the Latino Faith-Based Initiative, and the Democratic Party Latino Initiative both called for Bruce's resignation from the legislature.<ref name=\"resign\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Critics call for Bruce's resignation after remark |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_35551___article.html/colorado_rep.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=22 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424122048/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_35551___article.html/colorado_rep.html |archive-date=24 April 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBruce defended his remarks as being factually accurate, citing dictionary definitions of \"illiterate\" and \"peasant\". Legislators briefly considered bringing a formal ethics complaint against him,<ref name=\"removed\">{{cite news |first=Steven K. |last=Paulson |title=Colo. lawmaker removed from podium over Mexicans remark |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gjejGz2ScBlo-Eccugkvp2u9HLZQD906JKB00 |work=Associated Press |date=21 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504235016/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gjejGz2ScBlo-Eccugkvp2u9HLZQD906JKB00 |archivedate=4 May 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"barred\">\n{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=Bruce barred from speaking after 'illiterate' remark |url=http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_9003612 |work=Denver Post |date=21 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080605122839/http://origin.denverpost.com/rapids/ci_9003612 |archive-date=5 June 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> but ultimately chose not to. Legislators responded to Bruce's propensity for generating controversy by declaring that they would \"start ignoring him\".<ref name=\"noprobe\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Hoover |title=No ethics probe for Bruce over Mexican comment |url=http://origin.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9014237 |work=Denver Post |date=22 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080607053757/http://origin.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9014237 |archive-date=7 June 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"wake\">{{cite news |first=Charlie |last=Brennan |title=Threats in Wake of Bruce Controversy |url=http://www.myfoxcolorado.com/myfox/pages/News/Detail?contentId=6379598&version=1&locale=EN-US&layoutCode=TSTY&pageId=3.2.1 |work=MyFoxColorado |date=23 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-26 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Rep. Curry requested additional law enforcement protection after receiving an influx of threatening messages from opponents of [[illegal immigration]].<ref name=\"threat\">{{cite news|first=Mike |last=Saccone |title=Legislator threatened over Bruce incident |url=http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/04/22/042308_1a_Curry.html |work=Grand Junction Sentinel |date=22 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-23 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080527165721/http://www.gjsentinel.com/news/content/news/stories/2008/04/22/042308_1a_Curry.html |archivedate=2008-05-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Bruce, however, received hundreds of largely positive email messages in response to news coverage of the controversy.<ref name=\"brigade\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Ingold |title=Brigade of Bruce defenders fires e-mail barrage |url=http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_9031798 |work=Denver Post |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-24 }}</ref><ref name=\"glance3\">{{cite news|first=Michael |last=Davidson |title=Legislative glance: Wednesday in Review |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/fallout_35607___article.html/glance_legislative.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524015346/http://www.gazette.com/articles/fallout_35607___article.html/glance_legislative.html |archivedate=2011-05-24 }}</ref> The following weekend, Bruce's comments were the target of a local protest in Colorado Springs attended by about 50.<ref name=\"quote\">{{cite news |first=Annette |last=Espinoza |title=Bruce quote sparks protest |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_9068166 |work=Denver Post |date=27 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-27 }}</ref><ref name=\"migrant\">{{cite news |first=Terry |last=Jessup |title=Migrant Workers Protest Bruce's 'Peasant' Comments |url=http://cbs4denver.com/local/bruce.migrant.workers.2.706714.html |work=CBS4Denver.com |date=27 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506085110/http://cbs4denver.com/local/bruce.migrant.workers.2.706714.html |archivedate=6 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nSeveral days later, Bruce submitted an amendment &mdash; facetiously drafted by the \"linguistic sensitivity codification commission\" &mdash; to another bill addressing immigration issues to substitute \"undocumented, temporary guest resident\" in place of \"illegal aliens\" in statutory language. The amendment was offered and defeated twice.<ref name=\"pc\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=A new, improved and PC Bruce |url=http://www.politicswest.com/23776/new_improved_and_pc_bruce |work=Denver Post |date=25 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907002213/http://www.politicswest.com/23776/new_improved_and_pc_bruce |archive-date=7 September 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"sensitive\">{{cite news |first=Jeremy |last=Pelzer |title=Bruce shows his sensitive side |url=http://www.politickerco.com/jeremypelzer/1006/bruce-shows-his-sensitive-side |work=PolitickerCO |date=25 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513011506/http://www.politickerco.com/jeremypelzer/1006/bruce-shows-his-sensitive-side |archive-date=13 May 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment complaint===\nOn April 30, Bruce was the subject of a sexual harassment complaint after a female legislative staffer alleged that he made inappropriate verbal comments towards her. After being formally confronted by House Speaker [[Andrew Romanoff]], Bruce was instructed to stay away from the woman who filed the complaint, according to reports by other representatives.<ref name=\"complaint\">{{cite news |first=Lynn |last=Bartels |title=Woman files sexual harassment complaint against embattled Bruce |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/apr/30/female-staffer-lodges-complaint-against-bruce/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=30 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-30 }}</ref><ref name=\"files\">{{cite news |first=Adam |last=Schrager |title=Bruce accused of sexually harassing staffer |url=http://www.9news.com/news/top-article.aspx?storyid=90954 |work=9News.com |date=30 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-30 }} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"accuses\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=Sources: Staffer accuses Bruce of sex harassment |url=http://www.denverpost.com/commented/ci_9114126?source=commented-news |work=Denver Post |date=1 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-05-01 }}</ref> Legislative leaders refused to publicly discuss the complaint,<ref name=\"complaint2\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=Complaint against Rep. Bruce still unclear |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9125801 |work=Denver Post |date=2 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-05-02 }}</ref> but Douglas Bruce stated in a radio interview that the incident in question involved only looking and smiling at a woman.<ref name=\"justlook\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Bruce says he \"just looked\" at woman |url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_9136176 |work=Denver Post |date=2 May 2008 |accessdate=2008-05-03 }}</ref>\n\nAfter both Bruce and the woman involved were interviewed by attorneys,<ref name=\"complaint3\">{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Newsome |title=Bruce cleared of sexual harassment |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_38455___article.html/woman_complaint.html |work=Denver Post |date=21 July 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080905221108/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_38455___article.html/woman_complaint.html |archive-date=5 September 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Bruce reported in July that the harassment complaint had been dismissed for lack of evidence,<ref name=\"dismissed\">{{cite news |first=Jessica |last=Fender |title=Harassment complaint dismissed, Bruce says  |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9943785 |work=Denver Post |date=21 July 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08 }}</ref> and suggested that the timing of the investigation's conclusion was politically motivated, coming just weeks before a contested primary race.<ref name=\"conspir\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=State Rep. Bruce smells a conspiracy  |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jul/22/state-rep-bruce-smells-a-conspiracy/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=22 July 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08 }}</ref>\n\n==2008 election==\nBruce announced in November 2007 that he would stand in the 2008 general election for the House District 15 seat.<ref name=\"among\">{{cite news\n |first=Julia C. \n |last=Martinez \n |title=Douglas Bruce among three vying for House seat \n |url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/opinion/2007/11/27/douglas-bruce-among-three-vying-for-house-seat/ \n |work=Denver Post \n |date=November 27, 2007 \n |accessdate=2007-11-27 \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080101124849/http://blogs.denverpost.com/opinion/2007/11/27/douglas-bruce-among-three-vying-for-house-seat/ \n |archivedate=2008-01-01 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref> He faces a challenge for the Republican nomination from attorney and [[Iraq War]] veteran Mark Waller.<ref name=\"wins\"/> Following the precedent of his county commission campaign four years earlier, Bruce funded his own campaign, refusing to accept private campaign donations;<ref name=\"polgab\">{{cite news |first=Pam |last=Zubeck |title=POLITIGAB: Bruce says no to dependency |url=http://www.gazette.com/news/parade_37868___article.html/crank_district.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=2 July 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524020206/http://www.gazette.com/news/parade_37868___article.html/crank_district.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 }}</ref> instead, Bruce donated over $30,000 of his own money to his campaign.<ref name=\"thous\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=POLITIGAB: Thousands spent in primary runs |url=http://www.gazette.com/news/candidates_39058___article.html/state_primary.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=7 August 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20110524043205/http://www.gazette.com/news/candidates_39058___article.html/state_primary.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 }}</ref> He did, however, unsuccessfully solicit donations for his charity, Active Citizens Together, from other lawmakers.<ref name=\"strife\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Hoover |title=Bruce's rival says strife fails voters  |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_9963889 |work=Denver Post |date=22 July 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08 }}</ref> Reflecting Bruce's status as a \"pariah\" among some Colorado Springs Republicans,<ref name=\"pariah\"/> Waller received endorsements or contributions during his campaign from at least five sitting state representatives, including [[Bob Gardner]],{{citation needed|date=August 2015}} [[Larry Liston]],<ref name=\"pariah\"/> and [[Marsha Looper]],<ref name=\"thous\"/> as well as former Sen. [[Ron May (Colorado legislator)|Ron May]]<ref name=\"trail\">\n{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=On the stump - February 29, 2008 |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/waller_33740___article.html/district_business.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=29 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-02 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130123215239/http://www.gazette.com/articles/waller_33740___article.html/district_business.html |archive-date=23 January 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n</ref> and Colorado Attorney General [[John Suthers]].{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}\n\nWaller outpolled Bruce by receiving 57% of the vote at the Republican assembly in March, claiming the top line on the August Republican primary ballot;<ref name=\"no2\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce knocked to No. 2 on the ballot |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33993___article.html/waller_saturday.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=8 March 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310224207/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_33993___article.html/waller_saturday.html |archivedate=10 March 2008 }}</ref> he was supported by some delegates who had voted for Bruce's legislative appointment months earlier.<ref name=\"werewrong\">{{cite news |first=Cara |last=DeGette |title=Former Douglas Bruce Supporter: 'We Were Wrong' |url=http://coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do;jsessionid=4D722AE30C0FD392D188670110FA2D33?diaryId=3644 |work=Colorado Confidential |date=5 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080426225334/http://coloradoconfidential.com/showDiary.do;jsessionid=4D722AE30C0FD392D188670110FA2D33?diaryId=3644 |archive-date=26 April 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"lipsink\"/> During his campaign, Waller did not draw a contrast on political positions with Bruce, but argued that Bruce's temperament caused him to be an ineffective legislator.<ref name=\"toughrace\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Waller has a tough fight in race with Douglas Bruce |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/tough_38171___article.html/waller_bruce.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=12 July 2007 |accessdate=2008-08-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524020508/http://www.gazette.com/articles/tough_38171___article.html/waller_bruce.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\nBruce faced criticism from House Democratic and Republican leaders in April for distributing campaign fliers critical of Waller to Republican representatives on the House floor. Although not a violation of the law or House rules, legislative leaders denounced the action as a breach of decorum and tradition.<ref name=\"fire\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Bruce draws fire over fliers |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_34830___article.html/house_fliers.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=1 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524020632/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_34830___article.html/house_fliers.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"rebuke\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Ingold |author2=Jessica Fender |title=Bruce fliers bring rebuke |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_8774429 |work=Denver Post |date=1 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-02 }}</ref> Waller also called for Bruce's resignation in April 2008, after Bruce's controversial comments about Mexican guest workers.<ref name=\"noprobe\"/> Bruce, in response, characterised Waller as a \"conformer\" rather than a \"reformer,\" and stated that his controversial actions were designed to draw attention to inappropriate legislative actions.<ref name=\"lipsink\">{{cite news |first=Karen E. |last=Crummy |title=Bruce's lip sinking his ship? |url=http://www.denverpost.com/search/ci_9099564 |work=Denver Post |date=30 April 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-30 }}</ref>\n\nShortly before the August primary, Bruce was again criticized by Waller for mailing flyers promoting his charity, Active Citizens Together, soliciting volunteers and donations for the charity and stating: \"to reform government, ACT with Douglas Bruce.\" Although Waller declared that the flyers were \"an obvious attempt at campaigning,\" he did not file a complaint with the [[Colorado Secretary of State]]'s office, as he believed no laws were actually broken; the flyers did not mention any of Bruce's elected positions.<ref name=\"jugular\">{{cite news |first=Pam |last=Zubeck |title=Politigab: Jeff Crank launches another radio ad |url=http://www.gazette.com/news/bruce_38016___article_news.html/waller_act.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=8 July 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130124172108/http://www.gazette.com/news/bruce_38016___article_news.html/waller_act.html |archivedate=24 January 2013 }}</ref> Bruce was also criticized for listing endorsements on his website from political officials who had endorsed his campaign for county commissioner, but not specifically endorsed his legislative campaign. After attention was called to the discrepancy, Bruce had the erroneous endorsements removed, citing an \"overzealous webmaster.\"<ref name=\"sayendor\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover |title=Backers named on Bruce Web site say endorsement from 2004  |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/jul/21/backers-named-bruce-web-site-say-endorsement-2004/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=21 July 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08 }}</ref>\n\nIn turn, Bruce filed several campaign finance complaints against Waller, all but one of which&mdash;an accusation that Waller improperly accepted a corporate donation&mdash;were dismissed.<ref name=\"faceoff\"/> The hearing on Bruce's complaint was postponed until after the primary, over Bruce's objection, but resulted in Waller being cited and fined for failing to disclose a campaign contribution.<ref name=\"failing\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Waller campaign fined for failing to report funds |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/waller_40196___article.html/campaign_schuck.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=4 September 2008 |accessdate=2008-09-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120606140434/http://www.gazette.com/articles/waller_40196___article.html/campaign_schuck.html |archivedate=6 June 2012 }}</ref> Bruce also criticized Waller for his failure to vote in several recent elections, including the 2004 general election.<ref name=\"faceoff\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Bruce, Waller face off |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/face_38692___article.html/republican_candidates.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=27 July 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524020810/http://www.gazette.com/articles/face_38692___article.html/republican_candidates.html |archivedate=24 May 2011 }}</ref>\n\nBruce was narrowly defeated for the Republican nomination in the August 12 party primary, taking only 48 percent of the vote to Waller's 52 percent.<ref name=\"defeats\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Waller defeats Bruce |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_39268___article_news.html/waller_republican.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=12 August 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130124002040/http://www.gazette.com/articles/bruce_39268___article_news.html/waller_republican.html |archivedate=24 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\nDemocrat Allison Hunter withdrew from the race in December 2007, arguing that Bruce's appointment by a vacancy committee gave him \"too great an advantage\" in general election;<ref name=\"hunter\">{{cite news |first=Carlyn Ray |last=Mitchell |title=Dem opens bid for commission seat |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/hunter_33631___article.html/county_seat.html\n|work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=27 February 2008 |accessdate=2008-03-02 }}</ref> Waller will face Democrat Michelle Maksimowicz in November 2008.<ref name=\"defeats\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|25em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Colorado House Career Of Douglas Bruce}}\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives|Bruce, Douglas Colorado House career]]\n[[Category:Tenures in political office by individual|Bruce, Douglas]]\n[[Category:2000s in Colorado]]\n", "name_user": "Muboshgu", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colorado_House_career_of_Douglas_Bruce"}
{"title_page": "Ria Formosa", "text_new": "{{Designation list\n| designation1 = Ramsar\n| designation1_date = 24 November 1980\n| designation1_number = 212<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ria Formosa|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/212|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n[[Image:Ria Formosa Castro Marim 02.jpg|thumb|250px|Ria Formosa from Castro Marim]]\nThe '''Ria Formosa''' [[lagoon]], located in the [[Algarve]], in southern [[Portugal]], is a system of barrier islands that communicates with the sea through six inlets.  Five of these inlets are natural and have mobility characteristics.  The sixth is an artificial inlet that was opened with the purpose of allowing easier access to the port of [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]].\n\nPresently the main inlet of the system is the Faro-Olh\u00e3o inlet, which was artificially opened. The process started in 1927 but only in 1952 were the engineering works completed and it assumed the present configuration.\n\nWithin the Ria Formosa system, different and sometimes antagonistic uses may be found. Part of the system is a Natural Park but Ria Formosa also plays an important role in the region's economy.  Beyond the tourist use the system also supports other economic activities like seafood farms (including [[grooved carpet shell]] harvesting) and the port of Faro.\n\nThe Ria Formosa is also a designated [[Conservation areas of Portugal|Natural Park]] of over 170 km\u00b2 and a stopping place for hundreds of different birds during the spring and autumn migratory periods.\n\nThe most important cities near the Ria Formosa are [[Tavira Municipality|Tavira]], [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]] and [[Olh\u00e3o]].\n\nThere are also some towns in this area, whose names are: [[Fuzeta]] (which belongs to the municipality of [[Olh\u00e3o]]), [[Santa Luzia (Tavira)|Santa Luzia]], [[Cabanas de Tavira]] (these last two belonging to [[Tavira Municipality|Tavira]]) and [[Cacela Velha]] (which belongs to [[Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio Municipality|Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio]]).\n\nSeveral buses run from Tavira to Cabanas and back each weekday, but there are no buses on Saturday afternoons nor all day Sundays and Holidays, even in summer.  The nearest train station is in nearby [[Concei\u00e7\u00e3o (Tavira)|Concei\u00e7\u00e3o]] which is on the Tavira to Vila Real line. That's about {{convert|1|mi|km}} and an easy walk. Trains stop there daily, but at very irregular intervals of 1-3 h.\n\n== Entertainment ==\nLittle villages and towns in the area, such as [[Cabanas de Tavira]], have a large number of bars, caf\u00e9s and restaurants which run along the riverfront and are also dotted around a couple of blocks inland.\nAnnually, about 30'000 birds can be observed from Ria Formosa, since the region serves as a migratory corridor and contains some the last remaining nesting grounds in Europe for some bird species.\n\n== Beaches ==\n\nThe coast of east Algarve has a remarkably mild climate, with sunny days all year round.  Winters are usually mild and summers are not very hot.  Because of these features, beaches in the Ria Formosa area are well known, like [[Vale do Lobo]], [[Faro Island]], [[Culatra]], [[Barril (Tavira)|Barril]], [[Tavira Island]], [[Cabanas de Tavira]], [[Cacela Velha]] and [[Manta Rota]].  Barril attracts a good number of [[naturist]]s. Tavira Island Beach has a camping park.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons|Ria Formosa, Portugal|Ria Formosa}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cYl0GSA3kzI Video showing the train trip to Praia do Barril, located inside the natural park ]\n\n{{Protected areas of Portugal}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{coord|36.9833|N|7.91667|W|source:kolossus-ptwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Conservation in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Lagoons of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Ramsar sites in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Algarve]]\n[[Category:Geography of Faro District]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Faro District]]\n[[Category:Natura 2000 in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of Portugal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Designation list\n| designation1 = Ramsar\n| designation1_date = 24 November 1980\n| designation1_number = 212<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ria Formosa|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/212|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}\n[[Image:Ria Formosa Castro Marim 02.jpg|thumb|250px|Ria Formosa from Castro Marim]]\nThe '''Ria Formosa''' [[lagoon]], located in the [[Algarve]], in southern [[Portugal]], is a system of barrier islands that communicates with the sea through six inlets.  Five of these inlets are natural and have mobility characteristics.  The sixth is an artificial inlet that was opened with the purpose of allowing easier access to the port of [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]].\n\nPresently the main inlet of the system is the Faro-Olh\u00e3o inlet, which was artificially opened. The process started in 1927 but only in 1952 were the engineering works completed and it assumed the present configuration.\n\nWithin the Ria Formosa system, different and sometimes antagonistic uses may be found. Part of the system is a Natural Park but Ria Formosa also plays an important role in the region's economy.  Beyond the tourist use the system also supports other economic activities like seafood farms (including [[grooved carpet shell]] harvesting) and the port of Faro.\n\nThe Ria Formosa is also a designated [[Conservation areas of Portugal|Natural Park]] of over 170 km\u00b2 and a stopping place for hundreds of different birds during the spring and autumn migratory periods.\n\nThe most important cities near the Ria Formosa are [[Tavira Municipality|Tavira]], [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]] and [[Olh\u00e3o]].\n\nThere are also some towns in this area, whose names are: [[Fuzeta]] (which belongs to the municipality of [[Olh\u00e3o]]), [[Santa Luzia (Tavira)|Santa Luzia]], [[Cabanas de Tavira]] (these last two belonging to [[Tavira Municipality|Tavira]]) and [[Cacela Velha]] (which belongs to [[Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio Municipality|Vila Real de Santo Ant\u00f3nio]]).\n\nSeveral buses run from Tavira to Cabanas and back each weekday, but there are no buses on Saturday afternoons nor all day Sundays and Holidays, even in summer.  The nearest train station is in nearby [[Concei\u00e7\u00e3o (Tavira)|Concei\u00e7\u00e3o]] which is on the Tavira to Vila Real line. That's about {{convert|1|mi|km}} and an easy walk. Trains stop there daily, but at very irregular intervals of 1-3 h.\n\n== Entertainment ==\nLittle villages and towns in the area, such as [[Cabanas de Tavira]], have a large number of bars, caf\u00e9s and restaurants which run along the riverfront and are also dotted around a couple of blocks inland.\nAnnually, about 30'000 birds can be observed from Ria Formosa, since the region serves as a migratory corridor and contains some the last remaining nesting grounds in Europe for some bird species.\n\n== Beaches ==\n\nThe coast of east Algarve has a remarkably mild climate, with sunny days all year round.  Winters are usually mild and summers are not very hot.  Because of these features, beaches in the Ria Formosa area are well known, like [[Vale do Lobo]], [[Faro Island]], [[Culatra]], [[Barril (Tavira)|Barril]], [[Tavira Island]], [[Cabanas de Tavira]], [[Cacela Velha]] and [[Manta Rota]].  Barril attracts a good number of [[naturist]]s. Tavira Island Beach has a camping park.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons|Ria Formosa, Portugal|Ria Formosa}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cYl0GSA3kzI Video showing the train trip to Praia do Barril, located inside the natural park ]\n\n{{Protected areas of Portugal}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{coord|36.9833|N|7.91667|W|source:kolossus-ptwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Conservation in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Lagoons of Portugal]]\n[[Category:Ramsar sites in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Algarve]]\n[[Category:Geography of Faro District]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Faro District]]\n[[Category:Natura 2000 in Portugal]]\n", "name_user": "Zdtrlik", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ria_Formosa"}
