{"title_page": "Vilamoura", "text_new": "[[Image:MarinaVilamoura.JPG|thumb|180px|right| Marina of Vilamoura, Algarve, Portugal]]\n[[Image:Vilamoura.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Marina Beach in Vilamoura, Algarve, Portugal]]\n\n'''Vilamoura''' is an [[unincorporated area]] in [[Algarve]], on the southern coast of [[Portugal]]. It is one of the three corners of Algarve's [[Golden Triangle (Algarve)|Golden Triangle]]. Vilamoura comprises one of the largest single tourist complexes in Europe and with about 2,000 hectares of land. The nearest airport is in [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]].\n\nThe area previously hosted the annual [[Almond Blossom Cross Country]] competition between 1996 and 2003,<ref>Costa, Paulo (2005-01-31). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WXC/season=2005/eventCode=3363/news/kind=100/newsid=28373.html Kenyans Moses and Kiprop win in Algarve]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2010-03-10.</ref> and the same course was selected as the venue for the [[2000 IAAF World Cross Country Championships]].\n\n==History==\nThe resort developed around a small harbour, flanked by sandy beaches and close to the [[Roman ruins of Cerro da Vila]]. In Roman times this location was important in producing a fish paste known as \"garum\". The ruins also include the baths in which the mariners used to bathe.\n\nThe resort was founded by Portuguese banker [[:pt:Cupertino de Miranda|Cupertino de Miranda]] who, with the resort's management company Lusotur (now Lusort) started initial planning and building in 1966.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nIn 1996 Vilamoura (i.e. Lusotur) was acquired by [[Quinta do Lago]]'s Andre Jordan. In 2004 the resort was purchased by [[CatalunyaCaixa]].{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Facilities==\nVilamoura has the largest marina in Portugal (inaugurated in 1974) with 845 berths, two beaches, a Lawn Bowling Club with two grass greens, a Tennis Centre, a Sports Club, a Shooting Club, 5 Star and 4 Star Hotels, Tourist Apartments, self-catering Villas, Night Clubs, an International Casino with glamorous shows, and an excellent Riding School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-businessreport.com/article/a-booming-city-in-the-heart-of-the-algarve/ |title=A booming city in the heart of the Algarve |publisher=The Business Report  |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nWith five different golf courses, since 2016 in ownership of Dom Pedro Golf as a part of the [[Dom Pedro Hotels & Golf Collection|Dom Pedro Group]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portugalresident.com/2016/09/21/oceanico-group-sells-vilamoura-golf-courses/|title=Oc\u00eaanico Group sells Vilamoura golf courses|last=portugalpress|date=2016-09-21|website=Portugal Resident|language=en|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> Vilamoura is a very popular destination for golfers all year round.\n\n==Marina==\n[[Image:Vilamouro-Yachthafen.JPG|300px|thumb|left|Yachts in Vilamoura]]\nAt the heart of Vilamoura is the [[marina]] which has the capacity to berth over 1,000<ref>The AA Spiral Guide to the Algarve, by AA Publishing 2002.</ref> vessels. The marina is surrounded by large hotels and luxury holiday homes as well as a large [[casino]] and numerous restaurants and vibrant bars. At the far corner of the marina, it is possible to charter boats for big game fishing. There are also facilities for jet skiing and parascending. Close by there are also a number of sports clubs, a shooting range and many night clubs.\nTourism in Vilamoura is extensive and well-developed, with many different resorts with ratings from three to five stars. This is a substantially higher average than the surrounding areas, which have ratings varying from two to four. As a consequence of being mostly privately owned, the town is very opulently designed. The town and marina have an extensive variety of activities which are usually on Tuesdays, Thursdays and at weekends, including touring the local caves along the coastline (which are nearer to [[Albufeira]] than they are to Vilamoura). This cave tour is usually done on tour boats. The area also has two companies which operate trains-on-wheels for travel between resorts.\n\nFor the avid historians there is a preserved [[Cerro da Vila|Roman site]] and museum providing an insight to the area's past. Originally a Roman fishing town, the ruins include baths in which the mariners used to bathe.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nThe marina will be extended with Cidade Lacustre the new project that Lusort will be developing in Vilamoura in the next few years.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Vilamoura}}\n{{wikivoyage|Vilamoura}}\n\n* [https://www.dompedrogolf.com/ Official Website of Dom Pedro Golf]\n* [http://www.pbase.com/valterj/vilamoura Photos of Vilamoura]\n* [http://www.vilamouraportugal.org Vilamoura Essential Guide]\n* [http://www.portugal-book.com/algarve/vilamoura/index.htm Vilamoura Photos]\n* [http://www.vilamourauncovered.com/Portals/Vilamoura/map/map_vilamoura.pdf Vilamoura Map]\n* [http://www.360travelguide.com/360VirtualTour.asp?iCode=alg102 Panoramic Virtual Tour of Vilamoura Marina]\n\n{{coord|37|4|40|N|8|6|55|W|type:city_region:PT_source:nlwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Towns in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Marinas in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Loul\u00e9]]\n[[Category:Important Bird Areas of Portugal]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:MarinaVilamoura.JPG|thumb|180px|right| Marina of Vilamoura, Algarve, Portugal]]\n[[Image:Vilamoura.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Marina Beach in Vilamoura, Algarve, Portugal]]\n\n'''Vilamoura''' is an [[unincorporated area]] in [[Algarve]], on the southern coast of [[Portugal]]. It is one of the three corners of Algarve's [[Golden Triangle (Algarve)|Golden Triangle]]. Vilamoura comprises one of the largest single tourist complexes in Europe and with about 2,000 hectares of land. The nearest airport is in [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]].\n\nThe area previously hosted the annual [[Almond Blossom Cross Country]] competition between 1996 and 2003,<ref>Costa, Paulo (2005-01-31). [http://www.iaaf.org/history/WXC/season=2005/eventCode=3363/news/kind=100/newsid=28373.html Kenyans Moses and Kiprop win in Algarve]. [[IAAF]]. Retrieved on 2010-03-10.</ref> and the same course was selected as the venue for the [[2000 IAAF World Cross Country Championships]].\n\n==History==\nThe resort developed around a small harbour, flanked by sandy beaches and close to the [[Roman ruins of Cerro da Vila]]. In Roman times this location was important in producing a fish paste known as \"garum\". The ruins also include the baths in which the mariners used to bathe.\n\nThe resort was founded by Portuguese banker [[:pt:Cupertino de Miranda|Cupertino de Miranda]] who, with the resort's management company Lusotur (now Lusort) started initial planning and building in 1966.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nIn 1996 Vilamoura (i.e. Lusotur) was acquired by [[Quinta do Lago]]'s Andre Jordan. In 2004 the resort was purchased by [[CatalunyaCaixa]].{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\n==Facilities==\nVilamoura has the largest marina in Portugal (inaugurated in 1974) with 845 berths, two beaches, a Lawn Bowling Club with two grass greens, a Tennis Centre, a Sports Club, a Shooting Club, 5 Star and 4 Star Hotels, Tourist Apartments, self-catering Villas, Night Clubs, an International Casino with glamorous shows, and an excellent Riding School.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-businessreport.com/article/a-booming-city-in-the-heart-of-the-algarve/ |title=A booming city in the heart of the Algarve |publisher=The Business Report  |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nWith five different golf courses, since 2016 in ownership of Dom Pedro Golf as a part of the [[Dom Pedro Hotels & Golf Collection|Dom Pedro Group]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portugalresident.com/2016/09/21/oceanico-group-sells-vilamoura-golf-courses/|title=Oc\u00eaanico Group sells Vilamoura golf courses|last=portugalpress|date=2016-09-21|website=Portugal Resident|language=en|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref> Vilamoura is a very popular destination for golfers all year round.\n\n==Marina==\n[[Image:Vilamouro-Yachthafen.JPG|300px|thumb|left|Yachts in Vilamoura]]\nAt the heart of Vilamoura is the [[marina]] which has the capacity to berth over 1,000<ref>The AA Spiral Guide to the Algarve, by AA Publishing 2002.</ref> vessels. The marina is surrounded by large hotels and luxury holiday homes as well as a large [[casino]] and numerous restaurants and vibrant bars. At the far corner of the marina, it is possible to charter boats for big game fishing. There are also facilities for jet skiing and parascending. Close by there are also a number of sports clubs, a shooting range and many night clubs.\nTourism in Vilamoura is extensive and well-developed, with many different resorts with ratings from three to five stars. This is a substantially higher average than the surrounding areas, which have ratings varying from two to four. As a consequence of being mostly privately owned, the town is very opulently designed. The town and marina have an extensive variety of activities which are usually on Tuesdays, Thursdays and at weekends, including touring the local caves along the coastline (which are nearer to [[Albufeira]] than they are to Vilamoura). This cave tour is usually done on tour boats. The area also has two companies which operate trains-on-wheels for travel between resorts.\n\nFor the avid historians there is a preserved [[Cerro da Vila|Roman site]] and museum providing an insight to the area's past. Originally a Roman fishing town, the ruins include baths in which the mariners used to bathe.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nThe marina will be extended with Cidade Lacustre the new project that Lusort will be developing in Vilamoura in the next few years.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}